{"title_page": "Sankarabharanam (1980 film)", "text_new": "{{About|the 1980 Indian film|the eponymous raga|Shankarabharanam}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2015}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=October 2015}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Sankarabharanam\n| image          = sankarabharanam.jpg\n| film name = {{film name|te|\u0c36\u0c02\u0c15\u0c30\u0c3e\u0c2d\u0c30\u0c23\u0c02}}\n| director       = [[K. Viswanath]]\n| producer       = [[Edida Nageswara Rao]]<br/>Aakasam Sriramulu\n| writer         = K. Viswanath<br /> [[Jandhyala (filmmaker)|Jandhyala]] <small> (dialogues )</small>\n| screenplay     = K. Viswanath\n| starring       = [[J.V. Somayajulu]]<br />[[Manju Bhargavi]]<br />[[Chandra Mohan (Telugu actor)|Chandra Mohan]]\n| music          = [[K. V. Mahadevan]]\n| cinematography = [[Balu Mahendra]]\n| editing        = G. G. Krishna Rao\n| distributor    =[[Poornodaya Movie Creations]]\n| released       = {{film date|1980|02|02|df=y|ref1=}}\n| runtime        = 143 minutes{{sfn|Banerjee|Srivastava|1988|p=158}}\n| country        = India\n| language       = Telugu\n}}\n'''Sankarabharanam''' ({{lang-en|The Jewel of Shiva}}) is a 1980 Indian [[Telugu language|Telugu-language]] [[musical film|musical]] [[Drama (film and television)|drama film]] written and directed by [[K. Viswanath]]. Produced by Edida Nageswara Rao under the production company [[Poornodaya Movie Creations]], ''Sankarabharanam'' starred J. V. Somayajulu, Manju Bhargavi, Chandramohan and Rajyalakshmi. The soundtrack was composed by [[K. V. Mahadevan]] and remained a chartbuster. The film throws light on the chasm between Classical and Western Music based on the perspective of people from two different generations. \n\n''Sankarabharanam'' won the ''Prize of the Public'' at the \"[[Besan\u00e7on]] Film Festival of [[France]]\" in the year 1981.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://dff.nic.in/images/Documents/88_29thNfacatalogue.pdf|title=K. Viswanath Film craft Page 6 DFF|accessdate=2013-01-01}}</ref> It was screened at the ''[[8th International Film Festival of India]]'',<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://iffi.nic.in/Dff2011/Frm8IIFAAward.aspx?PdfName=8IIFA.pdf |title=8th IFFI Archived copy |access-date=2018-01-11 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180101233112/http://iffi.nic.in/Dff2011/Frm8IIFAAward.aspx?PdfName=8IIFA.pdf |archive-date=2018-01-01 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref> the ''[[Tashkent]] Film Festival'', the ''[[Asia Pacific Film Festival]]'', the ''[[Moscow International Film Festival]]'' held in May 1980,<ref>{{cite web|url= https://dff.nic.in/images/Documents/141_IPCatalogue1980-81.pdf|title=Filmtsav' 80 |publisher=DFF}}</ref><ref name=\"idlebrain.com\"/> and the ''[[Annapurna International School of Film and Media|AISFM Film Festival]]''.<ref>[http://www.aisfm.edu.in/blog/2014/the-films-of-k-viswanath/ The films of K. Viswanath \u2014 AISFM Blog<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> ''[[Forbes (India)|Forbes]]'' included J. V. Somayajulu's performance in the film on its list of \"25 Greatest Acting Performances of Indian Cinema\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://forbesindia.com/article/100-years-of-indian-cinema/25-greatest-acting-performances-of-indian-cinema/35125/0|title=25 Greatest Acting Performances of Indian Cinema|magazine=[[Forbes (India)|Forbes]]|first1=Shishir|last1=Prasad|first2=N. S.|last2=Ramnath|first3=Sohini|last3=Mitter|date=27 April 2013 |accessdate = 27 January 2015}}</ref> [[IBN Live]] included ''Sankarabharanam'' on its list of \"100 greatest Indian films of all time\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ibnlive.in.com/photogallery/13200.html|title=100 Years of Indian Cinema: The 100 greatest Indian films of all time|publisher=|accessdate=14 September 2016}}</ref>\n\n''Sankarabharanam'' became a [[sleeper hit]], having won four [[National Film Awards]] including the [[National Film Award for Best Popular Film Providing Wholesome Entertainment|Best Film with Mass Appeal, Wholesome Entertainment & Aesthetic Values]], the first for a ''South-Indian'' film at the [[27th National Film Awards]],<ref>{{cite book|title=Careers Digest|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=44vNAAAAMAAJ|accessdate=3 September 2013|year=1980|page=396}}</ref>and five state [[Nandi Awards]].<ref>{{cite book|title=Film World|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=WHpTAAAAYAAJ|accessdate=3 September 2013|year=1980|publisher=T.M. Ramachandran|page=217}}</ref> It was later dubbed into Tamil and Malayalam under the same title.<ref> name=\"idlebrain.com\"</ref>\n\n==Plot==\nThe film begins with an introduction by Viswanath in the form of a [[Sanskrit]] [[Subhashita]] \u0936\u093f\u0936\u0941\u0930\u094d\u0935\u0947\u0924\u094d\u0924\u093f \u092a\u0936\u0941\u0930\u094d\u0935\u0947\u0924\u094d\u0924\u093f \u0935\u0947\u0924\u094d\u0924\u093f \u0917\u093e\u0928\u0930\u0938\u0902 \u092b\u0923\u093f\u0903 (Music is enjoyed equally well by babies, animals and even snakes). We hope you appreciate our effort in bringing you the 'Jeeva Dhara' (Lifestream) of Indian classical music.\"\n\n\"Sankarabharanam\" Sankara Sastri is a very popular [[Carnatic music|Carnatic]] singer and a widower. People come in huge numbers to listen to his voice and consider him a great man. He has mastered the raga ''[[Shankarabharanam]]'' and hence is eponymous with the same. Tulasi, ([[Manju Bhargavi]]) is a Dasi's daughter who has great interest in music and dance.  She is also an admirer of Sastri, and goes to the riverbank in the early mornings when Sastri typically taught his own daughter.\n\nOne morning Tulasi is so thrilled by Sastri's singing that she begins dancing on the riverbank, oblivious of her surroundings.  Sastri sees her, and Tulasi also comes to her senses&nbsp;\u2014 and abruptly stops, expecting Sastri's rebuke.  But Sastri reciprocates her sincerity and continues singing&nbsp;\u2014 Thus is born an unspoken, platonic teacher-student relationship between the young dancer and the veteran singer.  This bond, bound to be misunderstood by a callous world, forms the crux of the story.\n\nTulasi's mother, of course, wants her to follow in the family profession by servicing rich clients.  The mother is waiting for the opportune time to introduce her daughter to prostitution, and one day she extracts a high price from a rich hedonist who's eager to be Tulasi's \"first\".  That man forces himself on Tulasi.  The foul deed done, the man sees a photo of Sastri in Tulasi's room and flings it to the ground while telling her that she's free to become the old Sastri's girlfriend now since he's done with her.  Tulasi, quiet until then, is ostensibly more hurt by the insult to Sastri, her [[guru]], than the crime perpetrated on herself.  She takes a shard of glass from the broken frame of Sastri's photo, and stabs the client.\n\nA murder trial ensues, and Sastri tries to save Tulasi by consulting his lawyer brother ([[Allu Ramalingaiah]]), who wins the case in Tulasi's favour.  Justice comes through as Tulasi's mother is sent to jail for unlawful flesh trade, while Tulasi is a free but homeless woman.  Sastri brings Tulasi to his home&nbsp;\u2014 precipitating changes in his own life.  The public, of course, assume that Sastri is keeping Tulasi at home as a mistress&nbsp;\u2014 and avoid him as a debauchee.  Even Sastri's maid and musical accompanists, who until then grudgingly bore the maestro's mentoring of \"that prostitute's daughter\", openly rebel and leave.  Tulasi feels responsible for Sastri's troubles, and eventually moves out of his house.\n\nSastri's problems are not all due to Tulasi, however.  The winds of change have made classical music wane in popularity, while [[pop music]] is on the ascendant.  Sastri loses his loyal audience and, with it, his comfortable lifestyle.  Ten years pass, and Sastri is living in a small house with his grown up daughter.  Meanwhile, by a quirk of fate, Tulasi has inherited her mother's property that was under litigation until then.  She wants to help the struggling Sastri anonymously. Tulasi has a ten-year-old son by then, ostensibly from her one-&-only conjugal encounter, and wishes that her son redeems his life by becoming Sastri's student&nbsp;\u2014 A chance she desperately wanted for herself, but was denied by Fate. So Tulasi gets her son to pretend to be homeless, and enter Sastri's household as a servant boy&nbsp;\u2014 and to earn his trust. Things go according to plan, and Tulasi is content to watch from a distance as her son gradually becomes a part of Sastri's household, and then his musical protege.\n\nPamulaparti Venkata Kameswara Rao ([[Chandra Mohan (Telugu actor)|Chandramohan]]), a [[Amateur|dilettante]] Brahmin boy, falls in love with Sastri's daughter.  Although Sastri rejects the alliance at first, he later agrees after learning of the man's interest in classical music.  Tulasi then arranges for a concert on the day of Sastri's daughter's wedding, where Sastri finds his lost audience return to hear his voice.  Sastri sings at the concert, but suffers a heart attack part-way through it.  Then his disciple, Tulasi's son, takes over from the sidelines and continues singing the song.. As Sastri watches his student with pride, he also sees Tulasi at the side of the hall, and realizes (via eye contact with his lawyer brother) that the boy is Tulasi's son. A doctor is brought to attend to Sastri, who is on stage clutching his chest with pain, but Sastri waves off the physician, knowing that his end is near. As Tulasi's son completes the song, Sastri symbolically anoints the boy as heir to his music, then dies&nbsp;\u2014 Tulasi comes running to her guru at that moment, and falls down at his feet&nbsp;\u2014 Moments later we realize that she too has died with the shock of Sastri's death. The film ends in this tragic but uplifting note, as the newly-weds Chandra Mohan & Sastri's daughter take charge of Tulasi's son.\n\n==Cast==\n{{col-begin}}{{col 2}}\n* [[J. V. Somayajulu]] <small>as</small> Sankarabharanam Sankara Sastry\n* [[Manju Bhargavi]] <small>as</small> Tulasi\n* [[Chandra Mohan (Telugu actor)|Chandra Mohan]] as Kameswar Rao\n* [[Rajalakshmi (actress)|Rajalakshmi]] <small>as</small> Sankara Sastry's daughter Sarada\n* [[Tulasi (actress)]] as Tulasi's son\n* [[Allu Ramalingaiah]] <small>as</small> Lawyer and Sankara Sastry's friend\n* [[Nirmalamma]]\n* [[Sakshi Ranga Rao]]\n* [[Dubbing Janaki]] (As cook)\n* Jith Mohan Mitra\n* Baby Varalakshmi <small>as</small> veena artist\n{{col 2}}\n* Jhansi <small>as</small> Tulasi's mother\n* Bhargahavi\n* Nirmalamma\n* Pushpa Kumari\n* Varalakshmi\n* Arja Janardhana Rao as Tulasi's maternal uncle\n* Edida Sriramprasad\n* S. Bheemeswara Rao\n* Dhum\n* Srigopal\n* Ganeswara Rao\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Crew==\n* Dialogues: [[Jandhyala]]\n* Lyrics: [[Veturi Sundararama Murthy]]\n* Playback Singers: [[S.P. Balasubramaniam]], [[S. Janaki]], [[Vani Jayaram]], [[S.P. Sailaja]], Madhavapeddi Ramesh, Jit Mohan Mitra & Pattabhi\n* Recording & Re-recording: A.R. Swaminathan\n* Dialogue Recording: Rajan & Kannan [Prasad Studios]\n* Production Managers: P. Rajagopal & Ravi Prakash\n* Makeup: Munduri Satyam\n* Hair stylist: P. Rama Murthy\n* Costumes: K. Surya Rao\n* Publicity: Ganagadhar & K.S. Pani\n* Press Relations: I. Arjuna Rao\n* Assistant Directors: [[Vamsy]] & J. Venkateswara Rao\n* Assistant Cameraman: Pandyan\n* Associate Editor: S. Nagababu\n* Stills: K. Satyanarayana\n* Art: [[Thota Tharani]]\n* Choreographer: V. Seshu Parupalli\n* Associate Director: Manduri Vijay\n* Editor: G. G. Krishna Rao\n* Director of photography: [[Balu Mahendra]]\n* Music Director: [[K.V. Mahadevan]]\n* Associate Producers: Thadi Ramakrishna, Thadi Haribabu, Thadi Babji\n* Producers: [[Edida Nageshwara Rao]] & Akasam Sreeramulu\n* Story, Screenplay & Direction: [[K. Viswanath]]\n\n==Production Companies==\n* Film Processing: Prasad Film Laboratories\n* Production Company: [[Poornodaya Movie Creations]]\n\n==Production==\nAfter hearing the plot, the producers were initially taken aback due to the [[parallel cinema]] tone to the subject matter, but finally [[Edida Nageswara Rao]] agreed to produce the film. He wanted [[Akkineni Nageswara Rao]] to enact the role of Sankara Sastry, [[K. Viswanath]] wanted [[Sivaji Ganesan]] to perform the role, but couldn't approach him for various reasons and also wanted [[Krishnam Raju]] for the role, but later refused as Viswanath felt his image as a star would ruin the role and he finally chosen a debutant [[J. V. Somayajulu]], a stage artist for the role.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.telugucinema.com/Original-choice-Sankarabharanam|title=Original choice for Sankarabharanam?|first=|last=admin|date=8 September 2014|publisher=|accessdate=14 September 2016}}</ref> [[Vamsy]], who went on to direct films like ''[[Sitaara]]'', ''[[Anveshana]]'' and ''[[Ladies Tailor (1985 film)|Ladies Tailor]]'' was one of the assistant directors in the film.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thehindu.com/features/metroplus/lessons-in-direction/article7642344.ece|title=Lessons in direction|first=B. Madhu|last=Gopal|date=11 September 2015|publisher=|accessdate=14 September 2016|via=The Hindu}}</ref>\n==Location==\nThe movies primary locations, as evident from the movie, is [[River Godavari]], then places in the river town of [[Rajahmundry]],<ref>''Sankarabharanam 35 Years Event'', 2015.[https://www.iqlikmovies.com/news/article/2015/02/19/sankarabharanam-movie-completes-35-years/7612]</ref> which include banks of river Godavari (Pushkar ghat) near [[Godavari (station)]], Shade Girls' High School, Augustus Hospital, [[Danavaipeta]] and other places.\n\n==Awards==\n{{awards table}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"10\"|1980\n| [[Edida Nageswara Rao]]\n| [[National Film Award for Best Popular Film Providing Wholesome Entertainment]]\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[K. V. Mahadevan]]\n| [[National Film Award for Best Music Direction]]\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[S. P. Balasubrahmanyam]]\n| [[National Film Award for Best Male Playback Singer]]\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[Vani Jayaram]]\n| [[National Film Award for Best Female Playback Singer]]\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[Edida Nageswara Rao]]\n| [[Nandi Award for Best Feature Film]] - Golden Nandi\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| S. P. Balasubrahmanyam\n| [[Nandi Award for Best Male Playback Singer]]\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[Veturi Sundararama Murthy]]<br>(\"Sankara Naada Sareerapara\")\n| [[Nandi Award for Best Lyricist]]\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[J. V. Somayajulu]]\n| [[Filmfare Award for Best Actor&nbsp;\u2013 Telugu]]\n| {{won}}\n|}\n\n==Soundtrack==\nThe music, largely [[Carnatic music|Carnatic]] based, was composed by [[K.V. Mahadevan]].\n[[M. Balamuralikrishna]] was the original choice for the male playback singer, due to the heavy classical content of the compositions. But K. V. Mahadevan, having faith in the mettle of [[S. P. Balasubrahmanyam]], insisted on him taking up this challenge.\n\n{{Tracklist\n| collapsed       =\n| headline        = Songs<ref>{{cite web|url=http://play.raaga.com/telugu/album/sankarabharanam-a0002322|title=Sankarabharanam songs|publisher=[[Raaga.com]]|accessdate=6 October 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141006120231/http://play.raaga.com/telugu/album/sankarabharanam-a0002322|archivedate=6 October 2014}}</ref>\n| extra_column    = Playback\n| all_music       = [[K. V. Mahadevan]]\n| title1  = [[Broche Varevaru Ra]]\n| lyrics1 = [[Mysore Vasudevachar]]\n| extra1  = [[S. P. Balasubrahmanyam]], [[Vani Jayaram]]\n\n| title2  = Dorakunaa Ituvanti Seva\n| lyrics2 = [[Veturi Sundararama Murthy]]\n| extra2  = S. P. Balasubrahmanyam. Vani Jayaram\n\n| title3  = Manasa Sancharare\n| lyrics3 = [[Sadasiva Brahmendra]]\n| extra3  = S. P. Balasubrahmanyam, Vani Jayaram\n\n| title4  = Maanikya Veena\n| note4   = Poem\n| lyrics4 = [[K\u0101lid\u0101sa|Mahakavi Kalidasu]]\n| extra4  = S. P. Balasubrahmanyam\n\n| title5  = Omkaara Naadaanusandhanam\n| lyrics5 = [[Veturi Sundararama Murthy]]\n| extra5  = S. P. Balasubrahmanyam, [[S. Janaki]]\n\n| title6  =  [[Paluke Bangaaramaayena]]\n| lyrics6 = [[Bhadrachala Ramadasu]]\n| extra6  = S. P. Balasubrahmanyam, Vani Jayaram\n\n| title7  = Raagam Taanam Pallavi\n| lyrics7 = Veturi Sundararama Murthy\n| extra7  = S. P. Balasubrahmanyam\n\n| title8  = Sankaraa Naadasareeraparaa\n| lyrics8 = Veturi Sundararama Murthy\n| extra8  = S. P. Balasubrahmanyam\n\n| title9  = Saamaja Varagamana\n| lyrics9 = Thyagaraja\n| extra9  = S. Janaki, S. P. Balasubrahmanyam\n\n| title10  = Ye Teeruga Nanu\n| lyrics10 = Bhadrachala Ramadasu\n| extra10  = Vani Jayaram\n}}\n\n==Release and reception==\nReleased on 2 February 1980, the film was released in only a very few theatres and opened to almost empty halls.<ref name=\"Telugu Cinema Etc&nbsp;\u2014 Idlebrain.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.idlebrain.com/celeb/interview/interview_gudipoodi.html|title=Telugu Cinema Etc - Idlebrain.com|publisher=|accessdate=14 September 2016}}</ref> However, due to positive word-of-mouth, the film opened to packed houses and had 365-day run at Royal theatre, [[Hyderabad, Andhra Pradesh|Hyderabad]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cinegoer.com/alltimelongrun.htm|title=CineGoer.com - Box-Office Records And Collections - All Time Long Run List|accessdate=14 September 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070515123606/http://www.cinegoer.com/alltimelongrun.htm|archivedate=15 May 2007|df=dmy-all}}</ref>, Alankar talkies, Bangalore etc\n\n==Legacy==\nThe success of this film triggered a sequence of classical films in Telugu, including ''[[Tyagayya (1981 film)|Tyagayya]]'' (by [[Bapu (artist)|Bapu]]), ''[[Meghasandesam]]'' (by Dasari N. Rao), and Viswanath's own follow-ups: ''[[Saptapadi (1981 film)|Saptapadi]]'',''[[Saagara Sangamam]]'', ''[[Shrutilayalu|Sruthi Layalu]]'', ''[[Swarna Kamalam]]'',''[[Swayam Krushi]]'', ''[[Sirivennela]]'', and ''[[Swati Kiranam]]''.<ref name=\"idlebrain.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.idlebrain.com/nosta/sankarabharanam.html|title=Telugu Cinema Nostalgia - Sankara Bharanam - JV Somayajulu, Manju Bhargavi and K Vishwanath|publisher=|accessdate=14 September 2016}}</ref> ''[[S.P. Balasubrahmanyam]]'', the Telugu playback singer who rendered all the songs of Sastri's character, has often said this movie was the highlight of his career. It got 'SPB' his first National Award, and made him a household name across all of South India. Film critic Gudipoodi Srihari called it as the best Telugu film he has seen after ''[[Mayabazar]]''.<ref name=\"Telugu Cinema Etc&nbsp;\u2014 Idlebrain.com\"/> Viswanath later remade the film in Hindi as ''[[Sur Sangam]]'' with [[Girish Karnad]], and [[Jaya Prada]] in the lead roles.<ref name=\"Telugu Cinema Etc&nbsp;\u2014 Idlebrain.com\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n* {{cite book | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zX4GY37rG8kC&pg=PA158&dq=Sankarabharanam&hl=en&sa=X&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=Sankarabharanam&f=false | title=One Hundred Indian Feature Films: An Annotated Filmography | publisher=[[Taylor & Francis]] | last=Banerjee | first=Shampa | last2=Srivastava | first2=Anil | year=1988 | isbn=0-8240-9483-2 | ref=harv}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|0079889}}\n\n{{National Film Award Wholesome Entertainment}}\n{{Kasinathuni Viswanath}}\n{{Jandhyala Subramanya Sastry}}\n[[Category:Indian films]]\n[[Category:Telugu-language films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by K. Viswanath]]\n[[Category:Social realism in film]]\n[[Category:Films about teacher\u2013student relationships]]\n[[Category:1980s musical drama films]]\n[[Category:Films about the arts]]\n[[Category:Films about classical music and musicians]]\n[[Category:Telugu film scores by K. V. Mahadevan]]\n[[Category:Best Popular Film Providing Wholesome Entertainment National Film Award winners]]\n[[Category:Indian nonlinear narrative films]]\n[[Category:Telugu films remade in other languages]]\n[[Category:Films about social issues in India]]\n[[Category:Indian musical drama films]]\n[[Category:Indian avant-garde and experimental films]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|the 1980 Indian film|the eponymous raga|Shankarabharanam}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2015}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=October 2015}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Sankarabharanam\n| image          = sankarabharanam.jpg\n| film name = {{film name|te|\u0c36\u0c02\u0c15\u0c30\u0c3e\u0c2d\u0c30\u0c23\u0c02}}\n| director       = [[K. Viswanath]]\n| producer       = [[Edida Nageswara Rao]]<br/>Aakasam Sriramulu\n| writer         = K. Viswanath<br /> [[Jandhyala (filmmaker)|Jandhyala]] <small> (dialogues )</small>\n| screenplay     = K. Viswanath\n| starring       = [[J.V. Somayajulu]]<br />[[Manju Bhargavi]]<br />[[Chandra Mohan (Telugu actor)|Chandra Mohan]]\n| music          = [[K. V. Mahadevan]]\n| cinematography = [[Balu Mahendra]]\n| editing        = G. G. Krishna Rao\n| distributor    =[[Poornodaya Movie Creations]]\n| released       = {{film date|1980|02|02|df=y|ref1=}}\n| runtime        = 143 minutes{{sfn|Banerjee|Srivastava|1988|p=158}}\n| country        = India\n| language       = Telugu\n}}\n'''Sankarabharanam''' ({{lang-en|The Jewel of Shiva}}) is a 1980 Indian [[Telugu language|Telugu-language]] [[musical film|musical]] [[Drama (film and television)|drama film]] written and directed by [[K. Viswanath]]. Produced by Edida Nageswara Rao under the production company [[Poornodaya Movie Creations]], ''Sankarabharanam'' starred J. V. Somayajulu, Manju Bhargavi, Chandramohan and Rajyalakshmi. The soundtrack was composed by [[K. V. Mahadevan]] and remained a chartbuster. The film throws light on the chasm between Classical and Western Music based on the perspective of people from two different generations. \n\n''Sankarabharanam'' won the ''Prize of the Public'' at the \"[[Besan\u00e7on]] Film Festival of [[France]]\" in the year 1981.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://dff.nic.in/images/Documents/88_29thNfacatalogue.pdf|title=K. Viswanath Film craft Page 6 DFF|accessdate=2013-01-01}}</ref> It was screened at the ''[[8th International Film Festival of India]]'',<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://iffi.nic.in/Dff2011/Frm8IIFAAward.aspx?PdfName=8IIFA.pdf |title=8th IFFI Archived copy |access-date=2018-01-11 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180101233112/http://iffi.nic.in/Dff2011/Frm8IIFAAward.aspx?PdfName=8IIFA.pdf |archive-date=2018-01-01 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref> the ''[[Tashkent]] Film Festival'', the ''[[Asia Pacific Film Festival]]'', the ''[[Moscow International Film Festival]]'' held in May 1980,<ref>{{cite web|url= https://dff.nic.in/images/Documents/141_IPCatalogue1980-81.pdf|title=Filmtsav' 80 |publisher=DFF}}</ref><ref name=\"idlebrain.com\"/> and the ''[[Annapurna International School of Film and Media|AISFM Film Festival]]''.<ref>[http://www.aisfm.edu.in/blog/2014/the-films-of-k-viswanath/ The films of K. Viswanath \u2014 AISFM Blog<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> ''[[Forbes (India)|Forbes]]'' included J. V. Somayajulu's performance in the film on its list of \"25 Greatest Acting Performances of Indian Cinema\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://forbesindia.com/article/100-years-of-indian-cinema/25-greatest-acting-performances-of-indian-cinema/35125/0|title=25 Greatest Acting Performances of Indian Cinema|magazine=[[Forbes (India)|Forbes]]|first1=Shishir|last1=Prasad|first2=N. S.|last2=Ramnath|first3=Sohini|last3=Mitter|date=27 April 2013 |accessdate = 27 January 2015}}</ref> [[IBN Live]] included ''Sankarabharanam'' on its list of \"100 greatest Indian films of all time\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ibnlive.in.com/photogallery/13200.html|title=100 Years of Indian Cinema: The 100 greatest Indian films of all time|publisher=|accessdate=14 September 2016}}</ref>\n\n''Sankarabharanam'' became a [[sleeper hit]], having won four [[National Film Awards]] including the [[National Film Award for Best Popular Film Providing Wholesome Entertainment|Best Film with Mass Appeal, Wholesome Entertainment & Aesthetic Values]], the first for a ''South-Indian'' film at the [[27th National Film Awards]],<ref>{{cite book|title=Careers Digest|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=44vNAAAAMAAJ|accessdate=3 September 2013|year=1980|page=396}}</ref>and five state [[Nandi Awards]].<ref>{{cite book|title=Film World|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=WHpTAAAAYAAJ|accessdate=3 September 2013|year=1980|publisher=T.M. Ramachandran|page=217}}</ref> It was later dubbed into Tamil and Malayalam under the same title.<ref> name=\"idlebrain.com\"</ref>\n\n==Plot==\nThe film begins with an introduction by Viswanath in the form of a [[Sanskrit]] [[Subhashita]] \u0936\u093f\u0936\u0941\u0930\u094d\u0935\u0947\u0924\u094d\u0924\u093f \u092a\u0936\u0941\u0930\u094d\u0935\u0947\u0924\u094d\u0924\u093f \u0935\u0947\u0924\u094d\u0924\u093f \u0917\u093e\u0928\u0930\u0938\u0902 \u092b\u0923\u093f\u0903 (Music is enjoyed equally well by babies, animals and even snakes). We hope you appreciate our effort in bringing you the 'Jeeva Dhara' (Lifestream) of Indian classical music.\"\n\n\"Sankarabharanam\" Sankara Sastri is a very popular [[Carnatic music|Carnatic]] singer and a widower. People come in huge numbers to listen to his voice and consider him a great man. He has mastered the raga ''[[Shankarabharanam]]'' and hence is eponymous with the same. Tulasi, ([[Manju Bhargavi]]) is a Dasi's daughter who has great interest in music and dance.  She is also an admirer of Sastri, and goes to the riverbank in the early mornings when Sastri typically taught his own daughter.\n\nOne morning Tulasi is so thrilled by Sastri's singing that she begins dancing on the riverbank, oblivious of her surroundings.  Sastri sees her, and Tulasi also comes to her senses&nbsp;\u2014 and abruptly stops, expecting Sastri's rebuke.  But Sastri reciprocates her sincerity and continues singing&nbsp;\u2014 Thus is born an unspoken, platonic teacher-student relationship between the young dancer and the veteran singer.  This bond, bound to be misunderstood by a callous world, forms the crux of the story.\n\nTulasi's mother, of course, wants her to follow in the family profession by servicing rich clients.  The mother is waiting for the opportune time to introduce her daughter to prostitution, and one day she extracts a high price from a rich hedonist who's eager to be Tulasi's \"first\".  That man forces himself on Tulasi.  The foul deed done, the man sees a photo of Sastri in Tulasi's room and flings it to the ground while telling her that she's free to become the old Sastri's girlfriend now since he's done with her.  Tulasi, quiet until then, is ostensibly more hurt by the insult to Sastri, her [[guru]], than the crime perpetrated on herself.  She takes a shard of glass from the broken frame of Sastri's photo, and stabs the client.\n\nA murder trial ensues, and Sastri tries to save Tulasi by consulting his lawyer brother ([[Allu Ramalingaiah]]), who wins the case in Tulasi's favour.  Justice comes through as Tulasi's mother is sent to jail for unlawful flesh trade, while Tulasi is a free but homeless woman.  Sastri brings Tulasi to his home&nbsp;\u2014 precipitating changes in his own life.  The public, of course, assume that Sastri is keeping Tulasi at home as a mistress&nbsp;\u2014 and avoid him as a debauchee.  Even Sastri's maid and musical accompanists, who until then grudgingly bore the maestro's mentoring of \"that prostitute's daughter\", openly rebel and leave.  Tulasi feels responsible for Sastri's troubles, and eventually moves out of his house.\n\nSastri's problems are not all due to Tulasi, however.  The winds of change have made classical music wane in popularity, while [[pop music]] is on the ascendant.  Sastri loses his loyal audience and, with it, his comfortable lifestyle.  Ten years pass, and Sastri is living in a small house with his grown up daughter.  Meanwhile, by a quirk of fate, Tulasi has inherited her mother's property that was under litigation until then.  She wants to help the struggling Sastri anonymously. Tulasi has a ten-year-old son by then, ostensibly from her one-&-only conjugal encounter, and wishes that her son redeems his life by becoming Sastri's student&nbsp;\u2014 A chance she desperately wanted for herself, but was denied by Fate. So Tulasi gets her son to pretend to be homeless, and enter Sastri's household as a servant boy&nbsp;\u2014 and to earn his trust. Things go according to plan, and Tulasi is content to watch from a distance as her son gradually becomes a part of Sastri's household, and then his musical protege.\n\nPamulaparti Venkata Kameswara Rao ([[Chandra Mohan (Telugu actor)|Chandramohan]]), a [[Amateur|dilettante]] Brahmin boy, falls in love with Sastri's daughter.  Although Sastri rejects the alliance at first, he later agrees after learning of the man's interest in classical music.  Tulasi then arranges for a concert on the day of Sastri's daughter's wedding, where Sastri finds his lost audience return to hear his voice.  Sastri sings at the concert, but suffers a heart attack part-way through it.  Then his disciple, Tulasi's son, takes over from the sidelines and continues singing the song.. As Sastri watches his student with pride, he also sees Tulasi at the side of the hall, and realizes (via eye contact with his lawyer brother) that the boy is Tulasi's son. A doctor is brought to attend to Sastri, who is on stage clutching his chest with pain, but Sastri waves off the physician, knowing that his end is near. As Tulasi's son completes the song, Sastri symbolically anoints the boy as heir to his music, then dies&nbsp;\u2014 Tulasi comes running to her guru at that moment, and falls down at his feet&nbsp;\u2014 Moments later we realize that she too has died with the shock of Sastri's death. The film ends in this tragic but uplifting note, as the newly-weds Chandra Mohan & Sastri's daughter take charge of Tulasi's son.\n\n==Cast==\n{{col-begin}}{{col 2}}\n* [[J. V. Somayajulu]] <small>as</small> Sankarabharanam Sankara Sastry\n* [[Manju Bhargavi]] <small>as</small> Tulasi\n* [[Chandra Mohan (Telugu actor)|Chandra Mohan]] as Kameswar Rao\n* [[Rajalakshmi (actress)|Rajalakshmi]] <small>as</small> Sankara Sastry's daughter Sarada\n* [[Tulasi (actress)]] as Tulasi's son\n* [[Allu Ramalingaiah]] <small>as</small> Lawyer and Sankara Sastry's friend\n* [[Nirmalamma]]\n* [[Sakshi Ranga Rao]]\n* [[Dubbing Janaki]] (As cook)\n* Jith Mohan Mitra\n* Baby Varalakshmi <small>as</small> veena artist\n{{col 2}}\n* Jhansi <small>as</small> Tulasi's mother\n* Bhargahavi\n* Nirmalamma\n* Pushpa Kumari\n* Varalakshmi\n* Arja Janardhana Rao as Tulasi's maternal uncle\n* Edida Sriramprasad\n* S. Bheemeswara Rao\n* Dhum\n* Srigopal\n* Ganeswara Rao\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Crew==\n* Dialogues: [[Jandhyala]]\n* Lyrics: [[Veturi Sundararama Murthy]]\n* Playback Singers: [[S.P. Balasubramaniam]], [[S. Janaki]], [[Vani Jayaram]], [[S.P. Sailaja]], Madhavapeddi Ramesh, Jit Mohan Mitra & Pattabhi\n* Recording & Re-recording: A.R. Swaminathan\n* Dialogue Recording: Rajan & Kannan [Prasad Studios]\n* Production Managers: P. Rajagopal & Ravi Prakash\n* Makeup: Munduri Satyam\n* Hair stylist: P. Rama Murthy\n* Costumes: K. Surya Rao\n* Publicity: Ganagadhar & K.S. Pani\n* Press Relations: I. Arjuna Rao\n* Assistant Directors: [[Vamsy]] & J. Venkateswara Rao\n* Assistant Cameraman: Pandyan\n* Associate Editor: S. Nagababu\n* Stills: K. Satyanarayana\n* Art: [[Thota Tharani]]\n* Choreographer: V. Seshu Parupalli\n* Associate Director: Manduri Vijay\n* Editor: G. G. Krishna Rao\n* Director of photography: [[Balu Mahendra]]\n* Music Director: [[K.V. Mahadevan]]\n* Associate Producers: Thadi Ramakrishna, Thadi Haribabu, Thadi Babji\n* Producers: [[Edida Nageshwara Rao]] & Akasam Sreeramulu\n* Story, Screenplay & Direction: [[K. Viswanath]]\n\n==Production Companies==\n* Film Processing: Prasad Film Laboratories\n* Production Company: [[Poornodaya Movie Creations]]\n\n==Production==\nAfter hearing the plot, the producers were initially taken aback due to the [[parallel cinema]] tone to the subject matter, but finally [[Edida Nageswara Rao]] agreed to produce the film. He wanted [[Akkineni Nageswara Rao]] to enact the role of Sankara Sastry, [[K. Viswanath]] wanted [[Sivaji Ganesan]] to perform the role, but couldn't approach him for various reasons and also wanted [[Krishnam Raju]] for the role, but later refused as Viswanath felt his image as a star would ruin the role and he finally chosen a debutant [[J. V. Somayajulu]], a stage artist for the role.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.telugucinema.com/Original-choice-Sankarabharanam|title=Original choice for Sankarabharanam?|first=|last=admin|date=8 September 2014|publisher=|accessdate=14 September 2016}}</ref> [[Vamsy]], who went on to direct films like ''[[Sitaara]]'', ''[[Anveshana]]'' and ''[[Ladies Tailor (1985 film)|Ladies Tailor]]'' was one of the assistant directors in the film.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thehindu.com/features/metroplus/lessons-in-direction/article7642344.ece|title=Lessons in direction|first=B. Madhu|last=Gopal|date=11 September 2015|publisher=|accessdate=14 September 2016|via=The Hindu}}</ref>\n==Location==\nThe movies primary locations, as evident from the movie, is [[River Godavari]], then places in the river town of [[Rajahmundry]],<ref>''Sankarabharanam 35 Years Event'', 2015.[https://www.iqlikmovies.com/news/article/2015/02/19/sankarabharanam-movie-completes-35-years/7612]</ref> which include banks of river Godavari (Pushkar ghat) near [[Godavari (station)]], Shade Girls' High School, Augustus Hospital, [[Danavaipeta]] and other places.\n\n==Awards==\n{{awards table}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"10\"|1980\n| [[Edida Nageswara Rao]]\n| [[National Film Award for Best Popular Film Providing Wholesome Entertainment]]\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[K. V. Mahadevan]]\n| [[National Film Award for Best Music Direction]]\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[S. P. Balasubrahmanyam]]\n| [[National Film Award for Best Male Playback Singer]]\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[Vani Jayaram]]\n| [[National Film Award for Best Female Playback Singer]]\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[Edida Nageswara Rao]]\n| [[Nandi Award for Best Feature Film]] - Golden Nandi\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| S. P. Balasubrahmanyam\n| [[Nandi Award for Best Male Playback Singer]]\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[Veturi Sundararama Murthy]]<br>(\"Sankara Naada Sareerapara\")\n| [[Nandi Award for Best Lyricist]]\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[J. V. Somayajulu]]\n| [[Filmfare Award for Best Actor&nbsp;\u2013 Telugu]]\n| {{won}}\n|}\n\n==Soundtrack==\nThe music, largely [[Carnatic music|Carnatic]] based, was composed by [[K.V. Mahadevan]].\n[[M. Balamuralikrishna]] was the original choice for the male playback singer, due to the heavy classical content of the compositions. But K. V. Mahadevan, having faith in the mettle of [[S. P. Balasubrahmanyam]], insisted on him taking up this challenge.\n\n{{Tracklist\n| collapsed       =\n| headline        = Songs<ref>{{cite web|url=http://play.raaga.com/telugu/album/sankarabharanam-a0002322|title=Sankarabharanam songs|publisher=[[Raaga.com]]|accessdate=6 October 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141006120231/http://play.raaga.com/telugu/album/sankarabharanam-a0002322|archivedate=6 October 2014}}</ref>\n| extra_column    = Playback\n| all_music       = [[K. V. Mahadevan]]\n| title1  = [[Broche Varevaru Ra]]\n| lyrics1 = [[Mysore Vasudevachar]]\n| extra1  = [[S. P. Balasubrahmanyam]], [[Vani Jayaram]]\n\n| title2  = Dorakunaa Ituvanti Seva\n| lyrics2 = [[Veturi Sundararama Murthy]]\n| extra2  = S. P. Balasubrahmanyam. Vani Jayaram\n\n| title3  = Manasa Sancharare\n| lyrics3 = [[Sadasiva Brahmendra]]\n| extra3  = S. P. Balasubrahmanyam, Vani Jayaram\n\n| title4  = Maanikya Veena\n| note4   = Poem\n| lyrics4 = [[K\u0101lid\u0101sa|Mahakavi Kalidasu]]\n| extra4  = S. P. Balasubrahmanyam\n\n| title5  = Omkaara Naadaanusandhanam\n| lyrics5 = [[Veturi Sundararama Murthy]]\n| extra5  = S. P. Balasubrahmanyam, [[S. Janaki]]\n\n| title6  =  [[Paluke Bangaaramaayena]]\n| lyrics6 = [[Bhadrachala Ramadasu]]\n| extra6  = S. P. Balasubrahmanyam, Vani Jayaram\n\n| title7  = Raagam Taanam Pallavi\n| lyrics7 = Veturi Sundararama Murthy\n| extra7  = S. P. Balasubrahmanyam\n\n| title8  = Sankaraa Naadasareeraparaa\n| lyrics8 = Veturi Sundararama Murthy\n| extra8  = S. P. Balasubrahmanyam\n\n| title9  = Saamaja Varagamana\n| lyrics9 = Thyagaraja\n| extra9  = S. Janaki, S. P. Balasubrahmanyam\n\n| title10  = Ye Teeruga Nanu\n| lyrics10 = Bhadrachala Ramadasu\n| extra10  = Vani Jayaram\n}}\n\n==Release and reception==\nReleased on 2 February 1980, the film was released in only a very few theatres and opened to almost empty halls.<ref name=\"Telugu Cinema Etc&nbsp;\u2014 Idlebrain.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.idlebrain.com/celeb/interview/interview_gudipoodi.html|title=Telugu Cinema Etc - Idlebrain.com|publisher=|accessdate=14 September 2016}}</ref> However, due to positive word-of-mouth, the film opened to packed houses and had a 216-day run at Royal theatre, [[Hyderabad, Andhra Pradesh|Hyderabad]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cinegoer.com/alltimelongrun.htm|title=CineGoer.com - Box-Office Records And Collections - All Time Long Run List|accessdate=14 September 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070515123606/http://www.cinegoer.com/alltimelongrun.htm|archivedate=15 May 2007|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Legacy==\nThe success of this film triggered a sequence of classical films in Telugu, including ''[[Tyagayya (1981 film)|Tyagayya]]'' (by [[Bapu (artist)|Bapu]]), ''[[Meghasandesam]]'' (by Dasari N. Rao), and Viswanath's own follow-ups: ''[[Saptapadi (1981 film)|Saptapadi]]'',''[[Saagara Sangamam]]'', ''[[Shrutilayalu|Sruthi Layalu]]'', ''[[Swarna Kamalam]]'',''[[Swayam Krushi]]'', ''[[Sirivennela]]'', and ''[[Swati Kiranam]]''.<ref name=\"idlebrain.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.idlebrain.com/nosta/sankarabharanam.html|title=Telugu Cinema Nostalgia - Sankara Bharanam - JV Somayajulu, Manju Bhargavi and K Vishwanath|publisher=|accessdate=14 September 2016}}</ref> ''[[S.P. Balasubrahmanyam]]'', the Telugu playback singer who rendered all the songs of Sastri's character, has often said this movie was the highlight of his career. It got 'SPB' his first National Award, and made him a household name across all of South India. Film critic Gudipoodi Srihari called it as the best Telugu film he has seen after ''[[Mayabazar]]''.<ref name=\"Telugu Cinema Etc&nbsp;\u2014 Idlebrain.com\"/> Viswanath later remade the film in Hindi as ''[[Sur Sangam]]'' with [[Girish Karnad]], and [[Jaya Prada]] in the lead roles.<ref name=\"Telugu Cinema Etc&nbsp;\u2014 Idlebrain.com\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n* {{cite book | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zX4GY37rG8kC&pg=PA158&dq=Sankarabharanam&hl=en&sa=X&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=Sankarabharanam&f=false | title=One Hundred Indian Feature Films: An Annotated Filmography | publisher=[[Taylor & Francis]] | last=Banerjee | first=Shampa | last2=Srivastava | first2=Anil | year=1988 | isbn=0-8240-9483-2 | ref=harv}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|0079889}}\n\n{{National Film Award Wholesome Entertainment}}\n{{Kasinathuni Viswanath}}\n{{Jandhyala Subramanya Sastry}}\n[[Category:Indian films]]\n[[Category:Telugu-language films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by K. Viswanath]]\n[[Category:Social realism in film]]\n[[Category:Films about teacher\u2013student relationships]]\n[[Category:1980s musical drama films]]\n[[Category:Films about the arts]]\n[[Category:Films about classical music and musicians]]\n[[Category:Telugu film scores by K. V. Mahadevan]]\n[[Category:Best Popular Film Providing Wholesome Entertainment National Film Award winners]]\n[[Category:Indian nonlinear narrative films]]\n[[Category:Telugu films remade in other languages]]\n[[Category:Films about social issues in India]]\n[[Category:Indian musical drama films]]\n[[Category:Indian avant-garde and experimental films]]\n", "name_user": "Tasarma", "label": "safe", "comment": "Addition of theatres that screened for 365 days", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sankarabharanam_(1980_film)"}
{"title_page": "Manchester United F.C. 9\u20130 Ipswich Town F.C.", "text_new": "{{short description|Association football match in England}}\n{{good article}}\n{{Infobox football match\n| title      = Manchester United v Ipswich Town\n| image      = [[File:Manchester United vs Ipswich Town (4 March 1995) programme.jpg|frameless]]\n| event      = [[1994\u201395 FA Premier League]]\n| team1      = [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]]\n| team1score = 9\n| team2      = [[Ipswich Town F.C.|Ipswich Town]]\n| team2score = 0\n| date       = 4 March 1995\n| stadium    = [[Old Trafford]]\n| city       = [[Manchester]]\n| referee    = [[Graham Poll]]\n| attendance = 43,804\n| weather    = \n}}\nThe [[association football|football]] match between [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] and [[Ipswich Town F.C.|Ipswich Town]] played at [[Old Trafford]], [[Manchester]], on 4 March 1995 as part of the [[1994\u201395 FA Premier League]] finished in a 9\u20130 victory for Manchester United.  The result stands alone as the record home win in the competition's history and the joint biggest win either home or away. The two teams went into the match at opposite ends of the table; Manchester United were second, while Ipswich Town were second from last. In the corresponding fixture at Ipswich's [[Portman Road]] ground earlier in the season, they had beaten United 3\u20132. Manchester United were missing [[Eric Cantona]], their French international [[Forward (association football)|forward]] who was serving a nine-month suspension, and their attacking partnership of [[Andy Cole]] and [[Mark Hughes]] was not well regarded. \n\nPlaying in front of the highest attendance in the league to that point in the season, United scored three times in the first half; [[Roy Keane]] opened the scoring, before Cole added two more. In the second half, United scored four times in the first twenty minutes; Cole scored his third and fourth, while Hughes also scored two. [[Paul Ince]] scored United's eighth with a [[Free kick (association football)|free kick]] into an empty net while Ipswich's goalkeeper [[Craig Forrest]] was arguing with the referee, before Cole scored a Premier League-record fifth goal, United's ninth, in the 89th minute. Ipswich finished the season in last place and were [[Promotion and relegation|relegated]] that season while Manchester United were second, one point behind champions [[Blackburn Rovers F.C.|Blackburn Rovers]].\n\n==Background==\n[[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] were the reigning [[Premier League]] champions, having won the [[1993\u201394 FA Premier League|1993\u201394 title]] by eight points ahead of [[Blackburn Rovers F.C.|Blackburn Rovers]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.soccerbase.com/tournaments/tournament.sd?tourn_id=120 |publisher=Racing Post |work=Soccerbase |title=Premiership 1993/94 |accessdate=14 April 2011 }}</ref> However, they had been knocked out of the [[1994\u201395 UEFA Champions League]] in the [[1994\u201395 UEFA Champions League group stage|group stage]],<ref name=\"cole-transfer\">{{cite news |first=David |last=Lacey |title=Ferguson invests \u00a37 million in Cole |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47000426/ |page=18 |work=The Guardian |via=Newspapers.com |date=11 January 1995 }}</ref> and were trailing Blackburn by three points at the top of the table going into this match.<ref name=\"table_1995-03-03\">{{cite web |url=https://www.11v11.com/league-tables/premier-league/03-march-1995/ |title=Historic league table generator \u2013 Premier League table after close of play on 03 March 1995 |website=11v11.com |publisher=AFS Enterprises |accessdate=20 March 2020 }}</ref> In response to their elimination from European competition, and their need for a goal-scorer, they signed [[Andy Cole]] from [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]] for a British record fee of \u00a37&nbsp;million in January 1995.<ref name=\"cole-transfer\"/>{{efn|The transfer for Cole was \u00a36&nbsp;million, plus the \u00a31&nbsp;million-rated [[Keith Gillespie]].<ref name=\"cole-transfer\"/>}}\n\n[[Ipswich Town F.C.|Ipswich Town]] had returned to the top flight of English football in time for the start of the Premier League in the [[1992\u201393 in English football|1992\u201393 season]];<ref>{{Cite news |first=Ruaidhr\u00ed |last=Croke |title=The 22 original Premier League teams: Where are they now? |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/sport/soccer/english-soccer/the-22-original-premier-league-teams-where-are-they-now-1.3181343 |work=[[Irish Times]] |date=10 August 2017 |accessdate=29 March 2020 }}</ref> however, they had finished in the bottom half of the table in both of the new league's first two seasons and had narrowly avoided relegation to the First Division in the final minutes of the 1993\u201394 campaign, finishing one point above the relegation zone.<ref>{{cite web |title=1993/94 Season Review |url=https://www.premierleague.com/history/1993-94 |website=premierleague.com |publisher=Premier League |accessdate=20 March 2020 }}</ref> Coming into this match, Ipswich were in 21st place in the league, three points and a game ahead of bottom club [[Leicester City F.C.|Leicester City]], but eight points away from escaping the relegation zone.<ref name=\"table_1995-03-03\"/>\n\nBefore this match, the two teams had met 50 times in all competitions; Manchester United had the upper hand with 24 wins to Ipswich's 18. The remaining eight matches, which finished as draws, were all in the league, where it was a similar story, with Manchester United winning 20 of the teams' 45 meetings, while Ipswich had 17 wins.<ref>{{cite web |title=United versus Ipswich Town |url=http://www.stretfordend.co.uk/opponents/ipswich.html |publisher=StretfordEnd.co.uk |accessdate=15 April 2010 }}</ref> The most recent game between the two sides, which was played at Ipswich's [[Portman Road]] ground on 24 September 1994, finished in a 3\u20132 win for Ipswich.<ref>{{cite news |first=Clive |last=White |title=Fracas as United fail |url=https://theguardian.newspapers.com/image/258483044/?terms=ipswich%2Bmanchester%2Bunited |page=70 |work=[[The Observer]] |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=21 March 2020 |date=25 September 1994 }}</ref> The Manchester United players were indignant at Ipswich's enthusiastic celebrations after the win:<ref name=\"daily-post\">{{cite news |url=https://www.dailypost.co.uk/sport/sport-opinion/inside-story-behind-manchester-uniteds-10111097 |title=The inside story behind Manchester United's 9\u20130 victory over Ipswich |last=Mitten |first=Andy |work=[[Daily Post (North Wales)|Daily Post]] |location=[[Colwyn Bay]] |date=22 September 2015 |accessdate=2 April 2020}}</ref> the United midfielder, [[Brian McClair]], said \"they were more than exuberant in their celebrations, so that stuck a bit\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thesportsman.com/articles/town-like-nine-pins-when-manchester-united-thrashed-ipswich-9-0-on-this-day-in-1995 |title=Town Like Nine Pins: When Manchester United Thrashed Ipswich 9\u20130 On This Day in 1995 |last=Crist |first=Matthew |work=The Sportsman |date=4 March 2018 |accessdate=2 April 2020}}</ref> In the period between the two sides' meetings that season, Ipswich had replaced [[John Lyall]] with [[George Burley]] as their manager.<ref>{{cite news |first=Andy |last=Martin |authorlink=Andy Martin (author) |title=Football: Beleaguered Ipswich pick Burley |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football-beleaguered-ipswich-pick-burley-1390876.html |work=[[The Independent]] |date=29 December 1994 |accessdate=21 March 2020 }}</ref>\n\nDespite this contrast in the fortunes of the two clubs, United had won just one of their four meetings with Ipswich in the first two seasons of the Premier League, being held to draws in both of Ipswich's visits to [[Old Trafford]], and losing 2\u20131 on their first Premier League visit to Portman Road in January 1993.<ref>{{cite web |title=Manchester United football club: record v Ipswich Town |url=https://www.11v11.com/teams/manchester-united/tab/opposingTeams/opposition/Ipswich%20Town/ |website=11v11.com |publisher=AFS Enterprises |accessdate=21 March 2020 }}</ref>\n\n==Team selection==\nIpswich selected a back four that featured [[David Linighan]], [[Neil Thompson]], [[John Wark]] and [[Frank Yallop]]; they had an average age of 32, and were described by ''[[The Guardian]]''{{'}}s Richard Barker as \"one of the slowest back fours the game has seen\".<ref name=\"wsc\">{{cite magazine |first=Richard |last=Barker |title=Caught in a landslide \u2013 Ipswich |url=https://www.wsc.co.uk/the-archive/30-Clubs/4565-caught-in-a-landslide--ipswich |issue=252 |date=February 2008 |accessdate=21 March 2020 |work=[[When Saturday Comes]]}}</ref> Up front, [[Lee Chapman]] started, but [[Paul Mason (footballer)|Paul Mason]] \u2013 who had scored twice during Ipswich's victory over United in September \u2013 was a substitute.<ref name=\"wsc\"/> Despite already having conceded 60 league goals that season, Burley had stated Ipswich's intention to attack: \"I'm certainly not going to put nine behind the ball. We'll play two up front and look to get forward\".<ref name=lifeafter>{{cite news |first=Christopher |last=Davies |title=There is life after Cole |url=https://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0001715/19950304/218/0017 |page=17 |work=[[Irish Independent]] |via=[[British Newspaper Archive]] |date=4 March 1995 |accessdate=22 March 2020 }}</ref>\n\nPrior to the game, Manchester United's Russian winger and season's top scorer [[Andrei Kanchelskis]] had handed in a [[transfer market|transfer request]], which was rejected by the United manager, [[Alex Ferguson]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Drugs shock of \u00a34m-rated striker Armstrong |url=https://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0002240/19950304/699/0059 |page=59 |work=[[The Journal (newspaper)|Newcastle Journal]] |via=[[British Newspaper Archive]] |date=4 March 1995 |accessdate=22 March 2020 }}</ref> Kanchelskis, along with [[Ryan Giggs]], Cole and [[Mark Hughes]], made up United's attack for the match. The pairing of Cole and Hughes up front was not considered well-matched; ''The Guardian''{{'}}s Stephen Bierley suggested that Cole was much better matched with [[Eric Cantona]],<ref>{{cite news |first=Stephen |last=Bierley |title=No pluses for United minus Cantona |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47216897/ |work=[[The Guardian]] |page=14 |via=Newspapers.com |date=27 February 1995 }}</ref> but the French [[Forward (association football)|forward]] was serving a nine-month suspension for kicking a spectator.<ref>{{cite news |first1=Robin |last1=Hackett |first2=Nick |last2=Atkin |title=When Manchester United's Eric Cantona attacked a fan in 1995 |url=https://www.espn.co.uk/football/english-premier-league/23/blog/post/2258750/when-manchester-uniteds-eric-cantona-attacked-a-fan-at-crystal-palace-rewind-to-1995 |work=ESPN |date=25 January 2018 |accessdate=23 March 2020 }}</ref> United had conceded just three league goals at Old Trafford all season.<ref name=hot/>\n\n==Match==\n===Summary===\n[[File:Andy Cole (13047502155) (cropped).jpg|thumb|upright|alt=Andy Cole|[[Andy Cole]] scored a Premier League record of five goals in the game.]]\nThe match took place at Old Trafford at 15:00 on 4 March 1995 in front of a crowd of 43,804, the largest in the league to date that season.<ref name=att>{{cite news |first=William |last=Johnson |title=Red Devils close to perfection |url=https://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0001715/19950306/318/0023 |page=23 |work=[[Irish Independent]] |via=[[British Newspaper Archive]] |date=6 March 1995 |accessdate=22 March 2020 }}</ref> Manchester United kicked off, attacking the [[Stretford End]] at the west end of the stadium, and within the first few minutes they had put the ball into the Ipswich [[penalty area]] five times; from three [[Cross (association football)|crosses]] and two [[corner kick]]s. According to Rogan Taylor's report for ''[[The Observer]]'', the Ipswich defence was panicked by these early attacks, and he suggested that Andy Cole should have scored from one of them, had he not accidentally stepped on the ball.<ref name=\"obs-report\">{{cite news |first=Rogan |last=Taylor |title=One over the eight |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46945457/ |page=70 |work=The Observer |via=Newspapers.com |date=5 March 1995 }}</ref> In the 15th minute, after an attack down the left wing, Hughes turned near the edge of the [[six-yard box]], and played the ball out to [[Roy Keane]] on the edge of the area. Keane kept his shot low, and it went in off the post.<ref name=\"obs-report\"/><ref name=\"ind-report\">{{cite news |first=Simon |last=O'Hagan |title=United's grand slam |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/uniteds-grand-slam-1609985.html |work=The Independent |date=5 March 1995 |accessdate=20 March 2020 }}</ref> Four minutes later, Giggs dispossessed Ipswich's Canadian right-back, Frank Yallop, on the halfway line. He broke clear and passed the ball to Cole, who rolled it in from three yards. In the 37th minute, Kanchelskis attacked up the right wing for Manchester United, and crossed the ball into the box; Hughes shot at goal with a [[bicycle kick]] that hit the bar and rebounded to Cole, who scored his second of the game and made it 3\u20130.<ref name=\"obs-report\"/> During his half-time team talk, Ferguson urged his team on, challenging them to score another three goals.<ref name=\"perfect\">{{cite news |url=https://readmanutd.com/2015/09/22/manchester-united-9-0-ipswich-town-perfect-victory/ |title=Manchester United 9\u20130 Ipswich Town \u2013 The Perfect Victory |last=Brown |first=Matthew |date=22 September 2015 |work=Read Man Utd |publisher=Fresh Press Media |accessdate=2 April 2020}}</ref> \n\nKeane was replaced with [[Lee Sharpe]] at half-time. Seven minutes after the break, Hughes passed the ball out to [[Denis Irwin]], who crossed it into the area. In the confusion, it was initially reported that Yallop had put the ball into his own goal,<ref name=\"obs-report\"/> but video replays showed that the final touch had been from Cole, securing his [[hat-trick]].<ref name=\"guard-report\">{{cite news |first=Stephen |last=Bierley |title=Cole flies over the moon |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46945930/ |page=18 |work=The Guardian |via=Newspapers.com |date=6 March 1995 }}</ref> Within a minute, a low cross from Giggs found Hughes, who scored United's fifth with a [[Volley (association football)|volley]] that went in off the crossbar. The pair were also responsible for United's next goal; the Ipswich goalkeeper [[Craig Forrest]] parried a shot from Giggs out to Hughes, who headed it in.<ref name=\"ind-report\"/> When [[Ian Marshall (English footballer)|Ian Marshall]] replaced Chapman in the 64th minute, Marshall thanked United's defender [[Gary Pallister]] \"for being invited to join the practice match\", according to an article  published by United.<ref name=\"perfect\"/> A minute later, Hughes helped to set up the seventh goal with a pass to McClair, whose shot was saved by Forrest but rebounded to Cole, who put it in the net.<ref name=\"ind-report\"/> In the 73rd minute, a foul was given against Forrest, who the referee, [[Graham Poll]], [[Penalty card#Yellow card|cautioned]] for handling the ball outside of his area. While Forrest was arguing the decision, Manchester United took the free kick quickly, and [[Paul Ince]] lobbed the ball straight into the empty goal to make the score 8\u20130. In the last few minutes of the match, Cole scored his fifth and United's ninth, from a corner delivered by Giggs.<ref name=\"obs-report\"/> The United fans chanted \"we want ten\", to which the away fans responded \"we want one\".<ref name=\"wsc\"/> The match finished 9\u20130 to Manchester United.<ref name=\"obs-report\"/>\n\n===Details===\n{{footballbox\n|date=4 March 1995\n|time=15:00\n|team1=[[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]]\n|score=9\u20130\n|report=<ref>{{cite book |editor1-first=Cliff |editor1-last=Butler |title=Manchester United Official Yearbook 1995 |year=1995 |publisher=Manchester United Football Club |location=Manchester |page=71 }}</ref>\n|team2=[[Ipswich Town F.C.|Ipswich Town]]\n|goals1=[[Roy Keane|Keane]] {{goal|16}}<br />[[Andy Cole|Cole]] {{goal|24||37||53||65||89}}<br />[[Mark Hughes|Hughes]] {{goal|54||59}}<br />[[Paul Ince|Ince]] {{goal|73}}\n|goals2=\n|stadium=[[Old Trafford]], [[Manchester]]\n|attendance=43,804\n|referee=[[Graham Poll]] ([[Berks & Bucks Football Association|Tilehurst]])\n}}\n\n{| width=92%\n|-\n|{{Football kit\n | pattern_la = _manutdh9496\n | pattern_b  = _manutdh9496\n | pattern_ra = _manutdh9496\n | pattern_sh = _manutdh9496\n | pattern_so = _manutdh9496\n | leftarm    = E20E0E\n | body       = E20E0E\n | rightarm   = E20E0E\n | shorts     = FFFFFF\n | socks      = 000000\n | title      = Manchester United\n}}\n|{{Football kit\n | pattern_la = _whiteborder\n | pattern_b  = _collarwhite\n | pattern_ra = _whiteborder\n | leftarm    = 003399\n | body       = 003399\n | rightarm   = 003399\n | shorts     = FFFFFF\n | socks      = 003399\n | title      = Ipswich Town\n}}\n|}\n\n{| width=\"100%\"\n|valign=\"top\" width=\"50%\"|\n{| style=\"font-size: 90%\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\"\n|-\n!width=\"25\"| !!width=\"25\"|\n|-\n|GK ||'''1''' ||{{flagicon|DEN}} [[Peter Schmeichel]]\n|-\n|RB ||'''16'''||{{flagicon|IRL}} [[Roy Keane]] || || {{suboff|46}}\n|-\n|CB ||'''4''' ||{{flagicon|ENG}} [[Steve Bruce]] ([[Captain (association football)|c]]) || || {{suboff|80}}\n|-\n|CB ||'''6''' ||{{flagicon|ENG}} [[Gary Pallister]]\n|-\n|LB ||'''3''' ||{{flagicon|IRL}} [[Denis Irwin]]\n|-\n|RM ||'''14'''||{{flagicon|RUS}} [[Andrei Kanchelskis]]\n|-\n|CM ||'''9''' ||{{flagicon|SCO}} [[Brian McClair]]\n|-\n|CM ||'''8''' ||{{flagicon|ENG}} [[Paul Ince]]\n|-\n|LM ||'''11'''||{{flagicon|WAL}} [[Ryan Giggs]]\n|-\n|CF ||'''17'''||{{flagicon|ENG}} [[Andy Cole]]\n|-\n|CF ||'''10'''||{{flagicon|WAL}} [[Mark Hughes]]\n|-\n|colspan=4|'''Substitutes:'''\n|-\n|GK ||'''13'''||{{flagicon|ENG}} [[Gary Walsh]]\n|-\n|MF ||'''5''' ||{{flagicon|ENG}} [[Lee Sharpe]] || || {{subon|46}}\n|-\n|MF ||'''19'''||{{flagicon|ENG}} [[Nicky Butt]] || || {{subon|80}}\n|-\n|colspan=4|'''Manager:'''\n|-\n|colspan=\"4\"|{{flagicon|SCO}} [[Alex Ferguson]]\n|}\n|valign=\"top\"|[[File:Man Utd vs Ipswich 1995-03-04.svg|300px]]\n|valign=\"top\" width=\"50%\"|\n{| style=\"font-size: 90%\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" align=center\n|-\n!width=\"25\"| !!width=\"25\"|\n|-\n|GK ||'''1''' ||{{flagicon|CAN}} [[Craig Forrest]] || {{yel|71}}\n|-\n|RB ||'''19'''||{{flagicon|CAN}} [[Frank Yallop]]\n|-\n|CB ||'''5''' ||{{flagicon|SCO}} [[John Wark]]\n|-\n|CB ||'''6''' ||{{flagicon|ENG}} [[David Linighan]] || {{yel|52}}\n|-\n|LB ||'''3''' ||{{flagicon|ENG}} [[Neil Thompson]]\n|-\n|RM ||'''18'''||{{flagicon|ENG}} [[Steve Palmer (footballer)|Steve Palmer]]\n|-\n|CM ||'''7''' ||{{flagicon|WAL}} [[Geraint Williams]]\n|-\n|CM ||'''14'''||{{flagicon|ENG}} [[Steve Sedgley]]\n|-\n|LM ||'''21'''||{{flagicon|ENG}} [[Stuart Slater]]\n|-\n|CF ||'''11'''||{{flagicon|ENG}} [[Lee Chapman]] || || {{suboff|64}}\n|-\n|CF ||'''33'''||{{flagicon|SCO}} [[Alex Mathie]]\n|-\n|colspan=4|'''Substitutes:'''\n|-\n|GK ||'''23'''||{{flagicon|ENG}} [[Phil Morgan (footballer)|Phil Morgan]]\n|-\n|MF ||'''4''' ||{{flagicon|ENG}} [[Paul Mason (footballer)|Paul Mason]]\n|-\n|FW ||'''10'''||{{flagicon|ENG}} [[Ian Marshall (English footballer)|Ian Marshall]] || || {{subon|64}}\n|-\n|colspan=4|'''Manager:'''\n|-\n|colspan=\"4\"|{{flagicon|SCO}} [[George Burley]]\n|}\n|}\n{| width=100% style=\"font-size: 90%\"\n|width=50% valign=top|\n'''Match officials'''\n*Linesmen:\n**M. A. Cooper (Walsall)\n**W. Markham (Blackburn)\n*Standby official:\n**A. S. Hogg (Sheffield)\n|width=50% valign=top|\n'''Match rules'''\n*90 minutes\n*No extra time or penalties\n*Three named substitutes\n*Maximum of two substitutions\n|}\n\n===Statistics===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align: center\"\n|+ Statistics<ref name=\"jervis\">{{cite book |editor1-first=Rachel |editor1-last=Jervis |title=Manchester United: Official Review of the 94/95 Season |year=1995 |publisher=Manchester United Football Club |location=Manchester |isbn=086369-814-X |pages=120\u20131 }}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" width=100|\n! scope=\"col\" width=70| Manchester United\n! scope=\"col\" width=70| Ipswich Town\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Goals scored \n| 9 || 0\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Shots on target \n| 14 || 1\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Shots off target \n| 7 || 5\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Free kicks \n| 8 || 10\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Offside \n| 3 || 2\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Fouls committed \n| 7 || 6\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Corner kicks \n| 8 || 4\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Yellow cards \n| 0 || 2\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Red cards \n| 0 || 0\n|}\n\n==Reaction==\nThe result was Manchester United's biggest league victory in 103 years, matching the nine-goal margin they recorded in a 10\u20131 win at home to [[Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C.|Wolverhampton Wanderers]] on 15 October 1892.<ref name=\"jervis\"/> Alex Ferguson had previously won twice 8\u20130 as [[Aberdeen F.C.|Aberdeen]] manager, but noted: \"That was as near as perfection as you can get. The performance superseded the number of goals scored.\"<ref name=hot>{{cite news |first=Eddie |last=Booth |title=Cole too hot to handle |url=https://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0002341/19950305/472/0079 |page=79 |via=[[British Newspaper Archive]] |work=[[Sunday Life (newspaper)|Sunday Life]] |date=5 March 1995 |accessdate=22 March 2020 }}</ref> He was later quoted as saying he was \"praying that United wouldn't reach ten, as he felt sorry for the Ipswich manager\".<ref>{{cite book |first=Michael |last=Crick |authorlink=Michael Crick |title=The Boss: The Many Sides of Alex Ferguson |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=jJFl52Whw34C&pg=PA386&lpg=PA386 |page=386 |publisher=Pocket Books |date=19 May 2003 |isbn=0-7434-2991-5 }}</ref> The Ipswich manager George Burley declined to face the press for the normal post-match interview.<ref>{{cite news |first=Martin |last=Lipton |authorlink=Martin Lipton |title=Five goal Cole |url=https://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0002324/19950305/631/0047 |page=47 |work=[[Sunday Independent (Ireland)|Sunday Independent]] |location=Dublin |via=[[British Newspaper Archive]] |date=5 March 1995 |accessdate=22 March 2020 }}</ref> The victory cancelled out Blackburn's goal difference advantage at the top of the table as Rovers beat [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]] 1\u20130 at [[Villa Park]] on the same day, although Rovers' manager [[Kenny Dalglish]] shrugged off the result saying, \"You only get three points whether you win 9\u20130 or 1\u20130.\"<ref>{{cite news |first=Nick |last=Miller |title=Top Tenner: Biggest wins in Premier League history |url=http://www.espnfc.co.uk/blog/espn-fc-united-blog/68/post/2096196/time-to-take-a-look-back-on-the-top-ten-biggest-wins-in-premier-league-history |work=ESPN FC |publisher=ESPN Internet Ventures |date=19 October 2014 |accessdate=26 June 2015 }}</ref> McClair referenced Ipswich's win earlier in the season, but denied that the scale of the win had been about revenge: \"it wasn\u2019t a case of: 'We're going to humiliate you and grind you into dust,' it was just: 'We're going to score as many as we can and keep going until it's over.' That\u2019s just the Manchester United way: it\u2019s never over.\"<ref name=\"perfect\"/>\n\nDespite taking a knock in a tackle by Ipswich defender Linighan, Cole was determined to play on in the second half despite his manager's suggestion he be substituted as the points were already secured. Cole noted: \"I sensed a hat-trick was there for the taking and I was determined to get one\".<ref name=att/> Cole's five-goal haul was later equalled by [[Alan Shearer]] \u2013 for Newcastle United against [[Sheffield Wednesday F.C.|Sheffield Wednesday]] in September 1999;<ref>{{cite web |title=Shear Magic \u2013 Alan's greatest moments! |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/tyne/content/articles/2006/01/17/shear_magic_feature.shtml |work=BBC Tyne |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |date=17 January 2006 |accessdate=15 July 2009 }}</ref> [[Jermain Defoe]] \u2013 for [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]] against [[Wigan Athletic F.C.|Wigan Athletic]] in November 2009;<ref>{{cite news |first=Paul |last=Fletcher |title=Tottenham Hotspur 9\u20131 Wigan Athletic|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/8365091.stm |work=BBC Sport |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |date=22 November 2009 |accessdate=22 November 2009 }}</ref> [[Dimitar Berbatov]] \u2013 for Manchester United against Blackburn Rovers in November 2010;<ref>{{cite news |first=Saj |last=Chowdhury |title=Manchester United 7\u20131 Blackburn Rovers|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/eng_prem/9221096.stm |work=BBC Sport |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |date=27 November 2010 |accessdate=27 November 2010 }}</ref> and [[Sergio Ag\u00fcero]] \u2013 for [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] against Newcastle United in October 2015.<ref>{{cite news |first=Chris |last=Bevan |title=Manchester City 6\u20131 Newcastle United|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/34366600 |publisher=BBC Sport (British Broadcasting Corporation) |date=3 October 2015 |accessdate=29 October 2015 }}</ref> Cole's haul was the first time for twelve years that a player in the top flight of English football had scored five goals in a game: [[Ian Rush]] and [[Tony Woodcock (footballer)|Tony Woodcock]] each scored five in separate matches on the same day in 1983.<ref>{{cite news |first=Steven |last=Pye |title=When Ian Rush and Tony Woodcock scored five goals on the same day |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/that-1980s-sports-blog/2018/oct/29/ian-rush-tony-woodcock-scored-five-goals-arsenal-liverpool |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=29 October 2018 |accessdate=22 March 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |first=Cliona |last=Foley |title=High five |url=https://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0001730/19950306/430/0052 |work=[[The Herald (Ireland)|Evening Herald]] |location=Dublin |date=6 March 1995 |accessdate=22 March 2020 }}</ref>\n\nManchester United went on to finish second in the league, just one point behind Blackburn, while Ipswich were relegated, finishing bottom of the table.<ref>{{cite web |title=Premiership 1994/95 |url=http://www.soccerbase.com/tournaments/tournament.sd?tourn_id=119 |publisher=Racing Post |work=Soccerbase |accessdate=13 April 2011 }}</ref> Ipswich goalkeeper Forrest went on to concede a further seven goals against Manchester United, playing for [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]] in a 7\u20131 defeat in April 2000.<ref>{{cite news |title=Scholes inspires rout of Hammers |work=BBC News |date=1 April 2000 |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/sport/football/fa_carling_premiership/697995.stm |accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref> Cole recalled that when he met Forrest years later, Forrest introduced Cole to his wife as \"the man who made his life a misery\".<ref name=\"daily-post\"/> The record Manchester United set for biggest Premier League win would not be equalled until Leicester City beat [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]] by the [[Southampton F.C. 0\u20139 Leicester City F.C.|same scoreline]], away from home on 25 October 2019.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/50092694|title=Southampton 0\u20139 Leicester City|publisher=BBC Sport |date=25 October 2019 |accessdate=25 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n'''Specific'''\n{{reflist}}\n\n'''General'''\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{cite video |people=[[Rob McCaffrey]], [[Tony Gubba]] |date=1995 |title=Record Breakers: Manchester United 9\u20130 Ipswich Town |medium=[[VHS]] |publisher=Granada Sports Television |asin=B000057K06 |asin-tld=co.uk }}\n{{refend}}\n\n{{1994\u201395 in English football}}\n{{Manchester United F.C. matches}}\n{{Ipswich Town F.C. matches}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Manchester United F.C. 9-0 Ipswich Town F.C.}}\n[[Category:1994\u201395 FA Premier League]]\n[[Category:Premier League matches|Manchester United v Ipswich Town 1995]]\n[[Category:Manchester United F.C. matches|Ipswich 1995]]\n[[Category:Ipswich Town F.C. matches|Manchester United 1995]]\n[[Category:Record association football wins]]\n[[Category:March 1995 sports events in the United Kingdom]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Association football match in England}}\n{{good article}}\n{{Infobox football match\n| title      = Manchester United v Ipswich Town\n| image      = [[File:Manchester United vs Ipswich Town (4 March 1995) programme.jpg|frameless]]\n| event      = [[1994\u201395 FA Premier League]]\n| team1      = [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]]\n| team1score = 9\n| team2      = [[Ipswich Town F.C.|Ipswich Town]]\n| team2score = 0\n| date       = 4 March 1995\n| stadium    = [[Old Trafford]]\n| city       = [[Manchester]]\n| referee    = [[Graham Poll]]\n| attendance = 43,804\n| weather    = \n}}\nThe [[association football|football]] match between [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] and [[Ipswich Town F.C.|Ipswich Town]] played at [[Old Trafford]], [[Manchester]], on 4 March 1995 as part of the [[1994\u201395 FA Premier League]] finished in a 9\u20130 victory for Manchester United.  The result stands alone as the record home win in the competition's history and the joint biggest win either home or away. The two teams went into the match at opposite ends of the table; Manchester United were second, while Ipswich Town were second from last. In the corresponding fixture at Ipswich's [[Portman Road]] ground earlier in the season, they had beaten United 3\u20132. Manchester United were missing [[Eric Cantona]], their French international [[Forward (association football)|forward]] who was serving a nine-month suspension, and their attacking partnership of [[Andy Cole]] and [[Mark Hughes]] was not well regarded. \n\nPlaying in front of the highest attendance in the league to that point in the season, United scored three times in the first half; [[Roy Keane]] opened the scoring, before Cole added two more. In the second half, United scored four times in the first twenty minutes; Cole scored his third and fourth, while Hughes also scored two. [[Paul Ince]] scored United's eighth with a [[Free kick (association football)|free kick]] into an empty net while Ipswich's goalkeeper [[Craig Forrest]] was arguing with the referee, before Cole scored a Premier League-record fifth goal, United's ninth, in the 89th minute. Ipswich finished the season in last place and were [[Promotion and relegation|relegated]] that season while Manchester United were second, one point behind champions [[Blackburn Rovers F.C.|Blackburn Rovers]].\n\n==Background==\n[[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] were the reigning [[Premier League]] champions, having won the [[1993\u201394 FA Premier League|1993\u201394 title]] by eight points ahead of [[Blackburn Rovers F.C.|Blackburn Rovers]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.soccerbase.com/tournaments/tournament.sd?tourn_id=120 |publisher=Racing Post |work=Soccerbase |title=Premiership 1993/94 |accessdate=14 April 2011 }}</ref> However, they had been knocked out of the [[1994\u201395 UEFA Champions League]] in the [[1994\u201395 UEFA Champions League group stage|group stage]],<ref name=\"cole-transfer\">{{cite news |first=David |last=Lacey |title=Ferguson invests \u00a37 million in Cole |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47000426/ |page=18 |work=The Guardian |via=Newspapers.com |date=11 January 1995 }}</ref> and were trailing Blackburn by three points at the top of the table going into this match.<ref name=\"table_1995-03-03\">{{cite web |url=https://www.11v11.com/league-tables/premier-league/03-march-1995/ |title=Historic league table generator \u2013 Premier League table after close of play on 03 March 1995 |website=11v11.com |publisher=AFS Enterprises |accessdate=20 March 2020 }}</ref> In response to their elimination from European competition, and their need for a goal-scorer, they signed [[Andy Cole]] from [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]] for a British record fee of \u00a37&nbsp;million in January 1995.<ref name=\"cole-transfer\"/>{{efn|The transfer for Cole was \u00a36&nbsp;million, plus the \u00a31&nbsp;million-rated [[Keith Gillespie]].<ref name=\"cole-transfer\"/>}}\n\n[[Ipswich Town F.C.|Ipswich Town]] had returned to the top flight of English football in time for the start of the Premier League in the [[1992\u201393 in English football|1992\u201393 season]];<ref>{{Cite news |first=Ruaidhr\u00ed |last=Croke |title=The 22 original Premier League teams: Where are they now? |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/sport/soccer/english-soccer/the-22-original-premier-league-teams-where-are-they-now-1.3181343 |work=[[Irish Times]] |date=10 August 2017 |accessdate=29 March 2020 }}</ref> however, they had finished in the bottom half of the table in both of the new league's first two seasons and had narrowly avoided relegation to the First Division in the final minutes of the 1993\u201394 campaign, finishing one point above the relegation zone.<ref>{{cite web |title=1993/94 Season Review |url=https://www.premierleague.com/history/1993-94 |website=premierleague.com |publisher=Premier League |accessdate=20 March 2020 }}</ref> Coming into this match, Ipswich were in 21st place in the league, three points and a game ahead of bottom club [[Leicester City F.C.|Leicester City]], but eight points away from escaping the relegation zone.<ref name=\"table_1995-03-03\"/>\n\nBefore this match, the two teams had met 50 times in all competitions; Manchester United had the upper hand with 24 wins to Ipswich's 18. The remaining eight matches, which finished as draws, were all in the league, where it was a similar story, with Manchester United winning 20 of the teams' 45 meetings, while Ipswich had 17 wins.<ref>{{cite web |title=United versus Ipswich Town |url=http://www.stretfordend.co.uk/opponents/ipswich.html |publisher=StretfordEnd.co.uk |accessdate=15 April 2010 }}</ref> The most recent game between the two sides, which was played at Ipswich's [[Portman Road]] ground on 24 September 1994, finished in a 3\u20132 win for Ipswich.<ref>{{cite news |first=Clive |last=White |title=Fracas as United fail |url=https://theguardian.newspapers.com/image/258483044/?terms=ipswich%2Bmanchester%2Bunited |page=70 |work=[[The Observer]] |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=21 March 2020 |date=25 September 1994 }}</ref> The Manchester United players were indignant at Ipswich's enthusiastic celebrations after the win:<ref name=\"daily-post\">{{cite news |url=https://www.dailypost.co.uk/sport/sport-opinion/inside-story-behind-manchester-uniteds-10111097 |title=The inside story behind Manchester United's 9\u20130 victory over Ipswich |last=Mitten |first=Andy |work=[[Daily Post (North Wales)|Daily Post]] |location=[[Colwyn Bay]] |date=22 September 2015 |accessdate=2 April 2020}}</ref> the United midfielder, [[Brian McClair]], said \"they were more than exuberant in their celebrations, so that stuck a bit\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thesportsman.com/articles/town-like-nine-pins-when-manchester-united-thrashed-ipswich-9-0-on-this-day-in-1995 |title=Town Like Nine Pins: When Manchester United Thrashed Ipswich 9\u20130 On This Day in 1995 |last=Crist |first=Matthew |work=The Sportsman |date=4 March 2018 |accessdate=2 April 2020}}</ref> In the period between the two sides' meetings that season, Ipswich had replaced [[John Lyall]] with [[George Burley]] as their manager.<ref>{{cite news |first=Andy |last=Martin |title=Football: Beleaguered Ipswich pick Burley |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football-beleaguered-ipswich-pick-burley-1390876.html |work=[[The Independent]] |date=29 December 1994 |accessdate=21 March 2020 }}</ref>\n\nDespite this contrast in the fortunes of the two clubs, United had won just one of their four meetings with Ipswich in the first two seasons of the Premier League, being held to draws in both of Ipswich's visits to [[Old Trafford]], and losing 2\u20131 on their first Premier League visit to Portman Road in January 1993.<ref>{{cite web |title=Manchester United football club: record v Ipswich Town |url=https://www.11v11.com/teams/manchester-united/tab/opposingTeams/opposition/Ipswich%20Town/ |website=11v11.com |publisher=AFS Enterprises |accessdate=21 March 2020 }}</ref>\n\n==Team selection==\nIpswich selected a back four that featured [[David Linighan]], [[Neil Thompson]], [[John Wark]] and [[Frank Yallop]]; they had an average age of 32, and were described by ''[[The Guardian]]''{{'}}s Richard Barker as \"one of the slowest back fours the game has seen\".<ref name=\"wsc\">{{cite magazine |first=Richard |last=Barker |title=Caught in a landslide \u2013 Ipswich |url=https://www.wsc.co.uk/the-archive/30-Clubs/4565-caught-in-a-landslide--ipswich |issue=252 |date=February 2008 |accessdate=21 March 2020 |work=[[When Saturday Comes]]}}</ref> Up front, [[Lee Chapman]] started, but [[Paul Mason (footballer)|Paul Mason]] \u2013 who had scored twice during Ipswich's victory over United in September \u2013 was a substitute.<ref name=\"wsc\"/> Despite already having conceded 60 league goals that season, Burley had stated Ipswich's intention to attack: \"I'm certainly not going to put nine behind the ball. We'll play two up front and look to get forward\".<ref name=lifeafter>{{cite news |first=Christopher |last=Davies |title=There is life after Cole |url=https://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0001715/19950304/218/0017 |page=17 |work=[[Irish Independent]] |via=[[British Newspaper Archive]] |date=4 March 1995 |accessdate=22 March 2020 }}</ref>\n\nPrior to the game, Manchester United's Russian winger and season's top scorer [[Andrei Kanchelskis]] had handed in a [[transfer market|transfer request]], which was rejected by the United manager, [[Alex Ferguson]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Drugs shock of \u00a34m-rated striker Armstrong |url=https://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0002240/19950304/699/0059 |page=59 |work=[[The Journal (newspaper)|Newcastle Journal]] |via=[[British Newspaper Archive]] |date=4 March 1995 |accessdate=22 March 2020 }}</ref> Kanchelskis, along with [[Ryan Giggs]], Cole and [[Mark Hughes]], made up United's attack for the match. The pairing of Cole and Hughes up front was not considered well-matched; ''The Guardian''{{'}}s Stephen Bierley suggested that Cole was much better matched with [[Eric Cantona]],<ref>{{cite news |first=Stephen |last=Bierley |title=No pluses for United minus Cantona |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47216897/ |work=[[The Guardian]] |page=14 |via=Newspapers.com |date=27 February 1995 }}</ref> but the French [[Forward (association football)|forward]] was serving a nine-month suspension for kicking a spectator.<ref>{{cite news |first1=Robin |last1=Hackett |first2=Nick |last2=Atkin |title=When Manchester United's Eric Cantona attacked a fan in 1995 |url=https://www.espn.co.uk/football/english-premier-league/23/blog/post/2258750/when-manchester-uniteds-eric-cantona-attacked-a-fan-at-crystal-palace-rewind-to-1995 |work=ESPN |date=25 January 2018 |accessdate=23 March 2020 }}</ref> United had conceded just three league goals at Old Trafford all season.<ref name=hot/>\n\n==Match==\n===Summary===\n[[File:Andy Cole (13047502155) (cropped).jpg|thumb|upright|alt=Andy Cole|[[Andy Cole]] scored a Premier League record of five goals in the game.]]\nThe match took place at Old Trafford at 15:00 on 4 March 1995 in front of a crowd of 43,804, the largest in the league to date that season.<ref name=att>{{cite news |first=William |last=Johnson |title=Red Devils close to perfection |url=https://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0001715/19950306/318/0023 |page=23 |work=[[Irish Independent]] |via=[[British Newspaper Archive]] |date=6 March 1995 |accessdate=22 March 2020 }}</ref> Manchester United kicked off, attacking the [[Stretford End]] at the west end of the stadium, and within the first few minutes they had put the ball into the Ipswich [[penalty area]] five times; from three [[Cross (association football)|crosses]] and two [[corner kick]]s. According to Rogan Taylor's report for ''[[The Observer]]'', the Ipswich defence was panicked by these early attacks, and he suggested that Andy Cole should have scored from one of them, had he not accidentally stepped on the ball.<ref name=\"obs-report\">{{cite news |first=Rogan |last=Taylor |title=One over the eight |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46945457/ |page=70 |work=The Observer |via=Newspapers.com |date=5 March 1995 }}</ref> In the 15th minute, after an attack down the left wing, Hughes turned near the edge of the [[six-yard box]], and played the ball out to [[Roy Keane]] on the edge of the area. Keane kept his shot low, and it went in off the post.<ref name=\"obs-report\"/><ref name=\"ind-report\">{{cite news |first=Simon |last=O'Hagan |title=United's grand slam |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/uniteds-grand-slam-1609985.html |work=The Independent |date=5 March 1995 |accessdate=20 March 2020 }}</ref> Four minutes later, Giggs dispossessed Ipswich's Canadian right-back, Frank Yallop, on the halfway line. He broke clear and passed the ball to Cole, who rolled it in from three yards. In the 37th minute, Kanchelskis attacked up the right wing for Manchester United, and crossed the ball into the box; Hughes shot at goal with a [[bicycle kick]] that hit the bar and rebounded to Cole, who scored his second of the game and made it 3\u20130.<ref name=\"obs-report\"/> During his half-time team talk, Ferguson urged his team on, challenging them to score another three goals.<ref name=\"perfect\">{{cite news |url=https://readmanutd.com/2015/09/22/manchester-united-9-0-ipswich-town-perfect-victory/ |title=Manchester United 9\u20130 Ipswich Town \u2013 The Perfect Victory |last=Brown |first=Matthew |date=22 September 2015 |work=Read Man Utd |publisher=Fresh Press Media |accessdate=2 April 2020}}</ref> \n\nKeane was replaced with [[Lee Sharpe]] at half-time. Seven minutes after the break, Hughes passed the ball out to [[Denis Irwin]], who crossed it into the area. In the confusion, it was initially reported that Yallop had put the ball into his own goal,<ref name=\"obs-report\"/> but video replays showed that the final touch had been from Cole, securing his [[hat-trick]].<ref name=\"guard-report\">{{cite news |first=Stephen |last=Bierley |title=Cole flies over the moon |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46945930/ |page=18 |work=The Guardian |via=Newspapers.com |date=6 March 1995 }}</ref> Within a minute, a low cross from Giggs found Hughes, who scored United's fifth with a [[Volley (association football)|volley]] that went in off the crossbar. The pair were also responsible for United's next goal; the Ipswich goalkeeper [[Craig Forrest]] parried a shot from Giggs out to Hughes, who headed it in.<ref name=\"ind-report\"/> When [[Ian Marshall (English footballer)|Ian Marshall]] replaced Chapman in the 64th minute, Marshall thanked United's defender [[Gary Pallister]] \"for being invited to join the practice match\", according to an article  published by United.<ref name=\"perfect\"/> A minute later, Hughes helped to set up the seventh goal with a pass to McClair, whose shot was saved by Forrest but rebounded to Cole, who put it in the net.<ref name=\"ind-report\"/> In the 73rd minute, a foul was given against Forrest, who the referee, [[Graham Poll]], [[Penalty card#Yellow card|cautioned]] for handling the ball outside of his area. While Forrest was arguing the decision, Manchester United took the free kick quickly, and [[Paul Ince]] lobbed the ball straight into the empty goal to make the score 8\u20130. In the last few minutes of the match, Cole scored his fifth and United's ninth, from a corner delivered by Giggs.<ref name=\"obs-report\"/> The United fans chanted \"we want ten\", to which the away fans responded \"we want one\".<ref name=\"wsc\"/> The match finished 9\u20130 to Manchester United.<ref name=\"obs-report\"/>\n\n===Details===\n{{footballbox\n|date=4 March 1995\n|time=15:00\n|team1=[[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]]\n|score=9\u20130\n|report=<ref>{{cite book |editor1-first=Cliff |editor1-last=Butler |title=Manchester United Official Yearbook 1995 |year=1995 |publisher=Manchester United Football Club |location=Manchester |page=71 }}</ref>\n|team2=[[Ipswich Town F.C.|Ipswich Town]]\n|goals1=[[Roy Keane|Keane]] {{goal|16}}<br />[[Andy Cole|Cole]] {{goal|24||37||53||65||89}}<br />[[Mark Hughes|Hughes]] {{goal|54||59}}<br />[[Paul Ince|Ince]] {{goal|73}}\n|goals2=\n|stadium=[[Old Trafford]], [[Manchester]]\n|attendance=43,804\n|referee=[[Graham Poll]] ([[Berks & Bucks Football Association|Tilehurst]])\n}}\n\n{| width=92%\n|-\n|{{Football kit\n | pattern_la = _manutdh9496\n | pattern_b  = _manutdh9496\n | pattern_ra = _manutdh9496\n | pattern_sh = _manutdh9496\n | pattern_so = _manutdh9496\n | leftarm    = E20E0E\n | body       = E20E0E\n | rightarm   = E20E0E\n | shorts     = FFFFFF\n | socks      = 000000\n | title      = Manchester United\n}}\n|{{Football kit\n | pattern_la = _whiteborder\n | pattern_b  = _collarwhite\n | pattern_ra = _whiteborder\n | leftarm    = 003399\n | body       = 003399\n | rightarm   = 003399\n | shorts     = FFFFFF\n | socks      = 003399\n | title      = Ipswich Town\n}}\n|}\n\n{| width=\"100%\"\n|valign=\"top\" width=\"50%\"|\n{| style=\"font-size: 90%\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\"\n|-\n!width=\"25\"| !!width=\"25\"|\n|-\n|GK ||'''1''' ||{{flagicon|DEN}} [[Peter Schmeichel]]\n|-\n|RB ||'''16'''||{{flagicon|IRL}} [[Roy Keane]] || || {{suboff|46}}\n|-\n|CB ||'''4''' ||{{flagicon|ENG}} [[Steve Bruce]] ([[Captain (association football)|c]]) || || {{suboff|80}}\n|-\n|CB ||'''6''' ||{{flagicon|ENG}} [[Gary Pallister]]\n|-\n|LB ||'''3''' ||{{flagicon|IRL}} [[Denis Irwin]]\n|-\n|RM ||'''14'''||{{flagicon|RUS}} [[Andrei Kanchelskis]]\n|-\n|CM ||'''9''' ||{{flagicon|SCO}} [[Brian McClair]]\n|-\n|CM ||'''8''' ||{{flagicon|ENG}} [[Paul Ince]]\n|-\n|LM ||'''11'''||{{flagicon|WAL}} [[Ryan Giggs]]\n|-\n|CF ||'''17'''||{{flagicon|ENG}} [[Andy Cole]]\n|-\n|CF ||'''10'''||{{flagicon|WAL}} [[Mark Hughes]]\n|-\n|colspan=4|'''Substitutes:'''\n|-\n|GK ||'''13'''||{{flagicon|ENG}} [[Gary Walsh]]\n|-\n|MF ||'''5''' ||{{flagicon|ENG}} [[Lee Sharpe]] || || {{subon|46}}\n|-\n|MF ||'''19'''||{{flagicon|ENG}} [[Nicky Butt]] || || {{subon|80}}\n|-\n|colspan=4|'''Manager:'''\n|-\n|colspan=\"4\"|{{flagicon|SCO}} [[Alex Ferguson]]\n|}\n|valign=\"top\"|[[File:Man Utd vs Ipswich 1995-03-04.svg|300px]]\n|valign=\"top\" width=\"50%\"|\n{| style=\"font-size: 90%\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" align=center\n|-\n!width=\"25\"| !!width=\"25\"|\n|-\n|GK ||'''1''' ||{{flagicon|CAN}} [[Craig Forrest]] || {{yel|71}}\n|-\n|RB ||'''19'''||{{flagicon|CAN}} [[Frank Yallop]]\n|-\n|CB ||'''5''' ||{{flagicon|SCO}} [[John Wark]]\n|-\n|CB ||'''6''' ||{{flagicon|ENG}} [[David Linighan]] || {{yel|52}}\n|-\n|LB ||'''3''' ||{{flagicon|ENG}} [[Neil Thompson]]\n|-\n|RM ||'''18'''||{{flagicon|ENG}} [[Steve Palmer (footballer)|Steve Palmer]]\n|-\n|CM ||'''7''' ||{{flagicon|WAL}} [[Geraint Williams]]\n|-\n|CM ||'''14'''||{{flagicon|ENG}} [[Steve Sedgley]]\n|-\n|LM ||'''21'''||{{flagicon|ENG}} [[Stuart Slater]]\n|-\n|CF ||'''11'''||{{flagicon|ENG}} [[Lee Chapman]] || || {{suboff|64}}\n|-\n|CF ||'''33'''||{{flagicon|SCO}} [[Alex Mathie]]\n|-\n|colspan=4|'''Substitutes:'''\n|-\n|GK ||'''23'''||{{flagicon|ENG}} [[Phil Morgan (footballer)|Phil Morgan]]\n|-\n|MF ||'''4''' ||{{flagicon|ENG}} [[Paul Mason (footballer)|Paul Mason]]\n|-\n|FW ||'''10'''||{{flagicon|ENG}} [[Ian Marshall (English footballer)|Ian Marshall]] || || {{subon|64}}\n|-\n|colspan=4|'''Manager:'''\n|-\n|colspan=\"4\"|{{flagicon|SCO}} [[George Burley]]\n|}\n|}\n{| width=100% style=\"font-size: 90%\"\n|width=50% valign=top|\n'''Match officials'''\n*Linesmen:\n**M. A. Cooper (Walsall)\n**W. Markham (Blackburn)\n*Standby official:\n**A. S. Hogg (Sheffield)\n|width=50% valign=top|\n'''Match rules'''\n*90 minutes\n*No extra time or penalties\n*Three named substitutes\n*Maximum of two substitutions\n|}\n\n===Statistics===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align: center\"\n|+ Statistics<ref name=\"jervis\">{{cite book |editor1-first=Rachel |editor1-last=Jervis |title=Manchester United: Official Review of the 94/95 Season |year=1995 |publisher=Manchester United Football Club |location=Manchester |isbn=086369-814-X |pages=120\u20131 }}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" width=100|\n! scope=\"col\" width=70| Manchester United\n! scope=\"col\" width=70| Ipswich Town\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Goals scored \n| 9 || 0\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Shots on target \n| 14 || 1\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Shots off target \n| 7 || 5\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Free kicks \n| 8 || 10\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Offside \n| 3 || 2\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Fouls committed \n| 7 || 6\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Corner kicks \n| 8 || 4\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Yellow cards \n| 0 || 2\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Red cards \n| 0 || 0\n|}\n\n==Reaction==\nThe result was Manchester United's biggest league victory in 103 years, matching the nine-goal margin they recorded in a 10\u20131 win at home to [[Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C.|Wolverhampton Wanderers]] on 15 October 1892.<ref name=\"jervis\"/> Alex Ferguson had previously won twice 8\u20130 as [[Aberdeen F.C.|Aberdeen]] manager, but noted: \"That was as near as perfection as you can get. The performance superseded the number of goals scored.\"<ref name=hot>{{cite news |first=Eddie |last=Booth |title=Cole too hot to handle |url=https://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0002341/19950305/472/0079 |page=79 |via=[[British Newspaper Archive]] |work=[[Sunday Life (newspaper)|Sunday Life]] |date=5 March 1995 |accessdate=22 March 2020 }}</ref> He was later quoted as saying he was \"praying that United wouldn't reach ten, as he felt sorry for the Ipswich manager\".<ref>{{cite book |first=Michael |last=Crick |title=The Boss: The Many Sides of Alex Ferguson |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=jJFl52Whw34C&pg=PA386&lpg=PA386 |page=386 |publisher=Pocket Books |date=19 May 2003 |isbn=0-7434-2991-5 }}</ref> The Ipswich manager George Burley declined to face the press for the normal post-match interview.<ref>{{cite news |first=Martin |last=Lipton |authorlink=Martin Lipton |title=Five goal Cole |url=https://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0002324/19950305/631/0047 |page=47 |work=[[Sunday Independent (Ireland)|Sunday Independent]] |location=Dublin |via=[[British Newspaper Archive]] |date=5 March 1995 |accessdate=22 March 2020 }}</ref> The victory cancelled out Blackburn's goal difference advantage at the top of the table as Rovers beat [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]] 1\u20130 at [[Villa Park]] on the same day, although Rovers' manager [[Kenny Dalglish]] shrugged off the result saying, \"You only get three points whether you win 9\u20130 or 1\u20130.\"<ref>{{cite news |first=Nick |last=Miller |title=Top Tenner: Biggest wins in Premier League history |url=http://www.espnfc.co.uk/blog/espn-fc-united-blog/68/post/2096196/time-to-take-a-look-back-on-the-top-ten-biggest-wins-in-premier-league-history |work=ESPN FC |publisher=ESPN Internet Ventures |date=19 October 2014 |accessdate=26 June 2015 }}</ref> McClair referenced Ipswich's win earlier in the season, but denied that the scale of the win had been about revenge: \"it wasn\u2019t a case of: 'We're going to humiliate you and grind you into dust,' it was just: 'We're going to score as many as we can and keep going until it's over.' That\u2019s just the Manchester United way: it\u2019s never over.\"<ref name=\"perfect\"/>\n\nDespite taking a knock in a tackle by Ipswich defender Linighan, Cole was determined to play on in the second half despite his manager's suggestion he be substituted as the points were already secured. Cole noted: \"I sensed a hat-trick was there for the taking and I was determined to get one\".<ref name=att/> Cole's five-goal haul was later equalled by [[Alan Shearer]] \u2013 for Newcastle United against [[Sheffield Wednesday F.C.|Sheffield Wednesday]] in September 1999;<ref>{{cite web |title=Shear Magic \u2013 Alan's greatest moments! |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/tyne/content/articles/2006/01/17/shear_magic_feature.shtml |work=BBC Tyne |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |date=17 January 2006 |accessdate=15 July 2009 }}</ref> [[Jermain Defoe]] \u2013 for [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]] against [[Wigan Athletic F.C.|Wigan Athletic]] in November 2009;<ref>{{cite news |first=Paul |last=Fletcher |title=Tottenham Hotspur 9\u20131 Wigan Athletic|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/8365091.stm |work=BBC Sport |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |date=22 November 2009 |accessdate=22 November 2009 }}</ref> [[Dimitar Berbatov]] \u2013 for Manchester United against Blackburn Rovers in November 2010;<ref>{{cite news |first=Saj |last=Chowdhury |title=Manchester United 7\u20131 Blackburn Rovers|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/eng_prem/9221096.stm |work=BBC Sport |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |date=27 November 2010 |accessdate=27 November 2010 }}</ref> and [[Sergio Ag\u00fcero]] \u2013 for [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] against Newcastle United in October 2015.<ref>{{cite news |first=Chris |last=Bevan |title=Manchester City 6\u20131 Newcastle United|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/34366600 |publisher=BBC Sport (British Broadcasting Corporation) |date=3 October 2015 |accessdate=29 October 2015 }}</ref> Cole's haul was the first time for twelve years that a player in the top flight of English football had scored five goals in a game: [[Ian Rush]] and [[Tony Woodcock (footballer)|Tony Woodcock]] each scored five in separate matches on the same day in 1983.<ref>{{cite news |first=Steven |last=Pye |title=When Ian Rush and Tony Woodcock scored five goals on the same day |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/that-1980s-sports-blog/2018/oct/29/ian-rush-tony-woodcock-scored-five-goals-arsenal-liverpool |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=29 October 2018 |accessdate=22 March 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |first=Cliona |last=Foley |title=High five |url=https://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0001730/19950306/430/0052 |work=[[The Herald (Ireland)|Evening Herald]] |location=Dublin |date=6 March 1995 |accessdate=22 March 2020 }}</ref>\n\nManchester United went on to finish second in the league, just one point behind Blackburn, while Ipswich were relegated, finishing bottom of the table.<ref>{{cite web |title=Premiership 1994/95 |url=http://www.soccerbase.com/tournaments/tournament.sd?tourn_id=119 |publisher=Racing Post |work=Soccerbase |accessdate=13 April 2011 }}</ref> Ipswich goalkeeper Forrest went on to concede a further seven goals against Manchester United, playing for [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]] in a 7\u20131 defeat in April 2000.<ref>{{cite news |title=Scholes inspires rout of Hammers |work=BBC News |date=1 April 2000 |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/sport/football/fa_carling_premiership/697995.stm |accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref> Cole recalled that when he met Forrest years later, Forrest introduced Cole to his wife as \"the man who made his life a misery\".<ref name=\"daily-post\"/> The record Manchester United set for biggest Premier League win would not be equalled until Leicester City beat [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]] by the [[Southampton F.C. 0\u20139 Leicester City F.C.|same scoreline]], away from home on 25 October 2019.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/50092694|title=Southampton 0\u20139 Leicester City|publisher=BBC Sport |date=25 October 2019 |accessdate=25 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n'''Specific'''\n{{reflist}}\n\n'''General'''\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{cite video |people=[[Rob McCaffrey]], [[Tony Gubba]] |date=1995 |title=Record Breakers: Manchester United 9\u20130 Ipswich Town |medium=[[VHS]] |publisher=Granada Sports Television |asin=B000057K06 |asin-tld=co.uk }}\n{{refend}}\n\n{{1994\u201395 in English football}}\n{{Manchester United F.C. matches}}\n{{Ipswich Town F.C. matches}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Manchester United F.C. 9-0 Ipswich Town F.C.}}\n[[Category:1994\u201395 FA Premier League]]\n[[Category:Premier League matches|Manchester United v Ipswich Town 1995]]\n[[Category:Manchester United F.C. matches|Ipswich 1995]]\n[[Category:Ipswich Town F.C. matches|Manchester United 1995]]\n[[Category:Record association football wins]]\n[[Category:March 1995 sports events in the United Kingdom]]\n", "name_user": "Harrias", "label": "safe", "comment": "ce refs", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Manchester_United_F.C._9%E2%80%930_Ipswich_Town_F.C."}
{"title_page": "Simele", "text_new": "{{Infobox settlement\n|pushpin_map = Iraqi Kurdistan#Iraq\n|pushpin_label_position =bottom\n|pushpin_mapsize        = \n|pushpin_map_caption    =Location in Iraq\n|official_name          = Simele\n|other_name             = \n|native_name            =\n|nickname               =\n|settlement_type        = <!--For Town or Village (Leave blank for the default City)-->\n|motto                  =\n|image          =\n|image_caption          = \n|population        = 71,600\n|population_as_of  = 2018\n|subdivision_type       = Country\n|subdivision_name       = {{flag|Iraq}}\n|subdivision_type1      = Autonomous region\n|subdivision_name1      = {{flag|Kurdistan Region}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://krg.org/articles/detail.asp?lngnr=12&smap=03010300&rnr=140&anr=23911 |title=Kurdistan Regional Government |publisher=KRG |date= |accessdate=2012-05-21}}</ref>\n|subdivision_type2      = Governorate\n|subdivision_name2      = [[Dohuk Governorate]]\n|coordinates            = {{coord|36|51|30|N|42|51|0.35|E|region:IQ|display=inline,title}}\n}}\n\n'''Simele''' ({{lang-syr|'''\u0723\u0721\u0720\u0710'''}}({{lang-ku|S\u00eam\u00eal ,\u0633\u06ce\u0645\u06ce\u0644}})<ref>{{cite book |title=Journal asiatique |date=1910 |publisher=Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 asiatique |location=Paris, France |page=131}}</ref> is a [[Kurds|Kurdish]]<ref>{{cite news |title=The Simele Massacre & the Unsung Hero of the Genocide Convention |url=https://www.nationalreview.com/2018/07/simele-massacre-1933-assyrian-victims-still-seek-justice/ |accessdate=29 March 2020 |agency=[[National Review]] |date=27 July 2018}}</ref> and [[Assyrian people|Assyrian]]<ref>{{cite book |author1=Ronald Sempill Stafford |title=The Tragedy of the Assyrian Minority in Iraq |date=1935 |page=187}}</ref> town located in the [[Dohuk Governorate|Dohuk province]] of [[Kurdistan Region]] in northern [[Iraq]]. The town is on the main road that connects [[Kurdistan Region]] to its neighbour [[Turkey]]. It is {{cvt|14|km}} west of the [[Dahuk, Iraq|city of Dohuk]].\n\n== Etymology ==\nThe town was mentioned by [[Yaqut al-Hamawi]] as \"Simwel\" which is thought to be a corruption of the Syriac ''Simm\u0101l\u0101'' ({{lang|syr|\u0723\u0721\u0720\u0710}}) meaning \"left\". Another possible origin could be the Syriac ''Shem\u02bb\u0113l'' ({{lang|syc|\u072b\u0721\u0725 \u0710\u071d\u0720}}), which means \"the name of God\".<ref>[http://www.ankawa.com/forum/index.php?topic=105353.0 \u0645\u062f\u064a\u0646\u0629 \u0633\u0645\u064a\u0644 \u0641\u064a \u0627\u0644\u062a\u0627\u0631\u064a\u062e], Ankawa.com {{in lang|ar}}</ref>{{better source needed|date=March 2020}}\n\n== History ==\nHistorically, the region in which Simele was a part of [[Assyria]] during its existence as a nation and then province from the 24th century BCE until the 7th century AD. The town was converted to Christianity in the 2nd century and was later famous for its [[Syriac language|Syriac]] manuscripts. Its [[Assyrian people|Assyrian]] inhabitants belonged to both the [[Syriac Orthodox Church]] and the [[Assyrian Church of the East]].<ref name=ankawa>[http://www.ankawa.com/forum/index.php?topic=105353.0 \u0645\u062f\u064a\u0646\u0629 \u0633\u0645\u064a\u0644 \u0641\u064a \u0627\u0644\u062a\u0627\u0631\u064a\u062e] Ankawa.com</ref> Its Assyrians inhabitants were joined by [[Yazidis]] who settled the town in 1800. Both were in turn massacred by Mir Muhammad of [[Rowanduz]]. Later on, [[Arabs|Arab]] tribes also started settling the area.<ref name=ankawa/>{{better source needed|date=March 2020}}\n\n===Simele massacre===\n{{Main|Simele massacre}}\nThe [[Assyrian people]], who resided in Simele and its neighbouring area, were subjected to [[Simele massacre|a massacre]] on August 7, 1933, implemented by the Iraqi government. The massacre was the first state-sponsored massacre in Iraq's young history after the establishment of Iraq in 1921. An estimated 3,000 [[Assyrian people|Assyrians]] died during the 1933 massacre,<ref>http://www.fidh.org/IMG/pdf/iq350a.pdf &mdash; [[FIDH]] report on ethnic cleansing in Iraq, which describes the Simele massacre in the second paragraph of page 17.</ref> most of them in the village of Simele. Thousands were forced to flee to [[Syria]] where the Assyrians went on to establish 33 villages in the [[Khabur (Euphrates)|Khabur]] plains of the [[Al-Jazira, Mesopotamia|Al Jazeera]] region, which still exist today.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Simele massacre]]\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Cities in Iraqi Kurdistan]]\n[[Category:Populated places in Dohuk Province]]\n[[Category:Assyrian communities in Iraq]]\n[[Category:Kurdish settlements]]\n[[Category:District capitals of Iraq]]\n{{Districts of Iraq}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox settlement\n|pushpin_map = Iraqi Kurdistan#Iraq\n|pushpin_label_position =bottom\n|pushpin_mapsize        = \n|pushpin_map_caption    =Location in Iraq\n|official_name          = Simele\n|other_name             = \n|native_name            =\n|nickname               =\n|settlement_type        = <!--For Town or Village (Leave blank for the default City)-->\n|motto                  =\n|image          =\n|image_caption          = \n|population        = 71,600\n|population_as_of  = 2018\n|subdivision_type       = Country\n|subdivision_name       = {{flag|Iraq}}\n|subdivision_type1      = Autonomous region\n|subdivision_name1      = {{flag|Kurdistan Region}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://krg.org/articles/detail.asp?lngnr=12&smap=03010300&rnr=140&anr=23911 |title=Kurdistan Regional Government |publisher=KRG |date= |accessdate=2012-05-21}}</ref>\n|subdivision_type2      = Governorate\n|subdivision_name2      = [[Dohuk Governorate]]\n|coordinates            = {{coord|36|51|30|N|42|51|0.35|E|region:IQ|display=inline,title}}\n}}\n\n'''Simele''' ({{lang-syr|'''\u0723\u0721\u0720\u0710'''}}{{transl|syr|''Simele''}}), ({{lang-ku|S\u00eam\u00eal ,\u0633\u06ce\u0645\u06ce\u0644}})<ref>{{cite book |title=Journal asiatique |date=1910 |publisher=Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 asiatique |location=Paris, France |page=131}}</ref> is a [[Kurds|Kurdish]]<ref>{{cite news |title=The Simele Massacre & the Unsung Hero of the Genocide Convention |url=https://www.nationalreview.com/2018/07/simele-massacre-1933-assyrian-victims-still-seek-justice/ |accessdate=29 March 2020 |agency=[[National Review]] |date=27 July 2018}}</ref> town and an [[Assyrian people|Assyrian]]<ref>{{cite book |author1=Ronald Sempill Stafford |title=The Tragedy of the Assyrian Minority in Iraq |date=1935 |page=187}}</ref> town located in the [[Dohuk Governorate|Dohuk province]] of [[Kurdistan Region]] in northern [[Iraq]]. The town is on the main road that connects [[Kurdistan Region]] to its neighbour [[Turkey]]. It is {{cvt|14|km}} west of the [[Dahuk, Iraq|city of Dohuk]].\n\n== Etymology ==\nThe town was mentioned by [[Yaqut al-Hamawi]] as \"Simwel\" which is thought to be a corruption of the Syriac ''Simm\u0101l\u0101'' ({{lang|syr|\u0723\u0721\u0720\u0710}}) meaning \"left\". Another possible origin could be the Syriac ''Shem\u02bb\u0113l'' ({{lang|syc|\u072b\u0721\u0725 \u0710\u071d\u0720}}), which means \"the name of God\".<ref>[http://www.ankawa.com/forum/index.php?topic=105353.0 \u0645\u062f\u064a\u0646\u0629 \u0633\u0645\u064a\u0644 \u0641\u064a \u0627\u0644\u062a\u0627\u0631\u064a\u062e], Ankawa.com {{in lang|ar}}</ref>{{better source needed|date=March 2020}}\n\n== History ==\nHistorically, the region in which Simele was a part of [[Assyria]] during its existence as a nation and then province from the 24th century BCE until the 7th century AD. The town was converted to Christianity in the 2nd century and was later famous for its [[Syriac language|Syriac]] manuscripts. Its [[Assyrian people|Assyrian]] inhabitants belonged to both the [[Syriac Orthodox Church]] and the [[Assyrian Church of the East]].<ref name=ankawa>[http://www.ankawa.com/forum/index.php?topic=105353.0 \u0645\u062f\u064a\u0646\u0629 \u0633\u0645\u064a\u0644 \u0641\u064a \u0627\u0644\u062a\u0627\u0631\u064a\u062e] Ankawa.com</ref> Its Assyrians inhabitants were joined by [[Yazidis]] who settled the town in 1800. Both were in turn massacred by Mir Muhammad of [[Rowanduz]]. Later on, [[Arabs|Arab]] tribes also started settling the area.<ref name=ankawa/>{{better source needed|date=March 2020}}\n\n===Simele massacre===\n{{Main|Simele massacre}}\nThe [[Assyrian people]], who resided in Simele and its neighbouring area, were subjected to [[Simele massacre|a massacre]] on August 7, 1933, implemented by the Iraqi government with help from Kurdish tribes. The massacre was the first state-sponsored massacre in Iraq's young history after the establishment of Iraq in 1921. An estimated 3,000 [[Assyrian people|Assyrians]] died during the 1933 massacre,<ref>http://www.fidh.org/IMG/pdf/iq350a.pdf &mdash; [[FIDH]] report on ethnic cleansing in Iraq, which describes the Simele massacre in the second paragraph of page 17.</ref> most of them in the village of Simele. Thousands were forced to flee to [[Syria]] where the Assyrians went on to establish 33 villages in the [[Khabur (Euphrates)|Khabur]] plains of the [[Al-Jazira, Mesopotamia|Al Jazeera]] region, which still exist today.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Simele massacre]]\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Cities in Iraqi Kurdistan]]\n[[Category:Populated places in Dohuk Province]]\n[[Category:Assyrian communities in Iraq]]\n[[Category:Kurdish settlements]]\n[[Category:District capitals of Iraq]]\n{{Districts of Iraq}}\n", "name_user": "Sems\u00fbr\u00ee", "label": "safe", "comment": "unsourced", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Simele"}
